former president carter an official observer of 
next months elections in nicaragua said monday hes confident the 
voting will be fair and honest 
i think its going to be relatively speaking a superb 
election carter just back from that central american country 
told a national security symposium at the carter presidential 
center 
what is protecting the integrity of the election is that both 
sides believe they are going to win he said referring to the 
sandinista government and the opposition 
carter has been invited to observe the general elections along 
with representatives of the council of freely elected heads of 
government a group of former chief executives which carter heads 
carter returned from a trip to nicaragua sunday night 
were doing everything we can to ensure that technically the 
election is almost perfect he said monday 
the sandinistas have been cooperative realizing they will not 
look good if carter and other international observers brand the 
elections as fixed 
the former president expressed the hope that the trend toward 
free elections might spread to cambodia afghanistan and other 
troubled nations 
this is the kind of approach that can be a new evolution in 
addressing longstanding armed conflict in troubled parts of the 
world carter said 
carter also said that with prodemocracy movements around the 
world the united states has an important opportunity to use 
these tremendous resources we have been wasting on weapons and 
sometimes spending wisely on weapons for other purposes 
he said the defense budget could be halved within a decade 
leaving an adequate military coupled with national security based 
on friendship and cooperation between nations 
will we do it he asked i dont know it might take 
us a year or two to realize we have this opportunity but such 
wonderful things can be done 
