<TEXT>
striking hotel workers briefly closed the main 
streeet downtown monday night in a noisy sitin that ended with 
police arresting 74 of the demonstrators 
the strikers linked arms and sat in a circle in the middle of 
glittering fremont street between the golden nugget and binions 
horseshoe club where union workers walked off the job saturday 
after working without a contract for eight months 
about 30 police officers confronted the strikers and after they 
refused to disband began arresting them one by one there was no 
violence and the demonstration was over in 30 minutes 
culinary union local 226 leader jim arnold was among those put 
in plastic handcuffs and taken to a waiting police bus for 
transportation to the clark county detention center 
metropolitan police lt randy oaks said the strikers arrested 
would be booked on misdemeanor public nuisance charges 
union officials said they had made arrangements to bail strikers 
out 
pickets marching in front of the horseshoe club chanted slogans 
in support of the strikers in the street as curious tourists 
sipped drinks and watched the action from the other side of the 
street 
the strike was the first by the culinary and bartenders unions 
since 1984 when a walkout against most of the citys resorts cost 
millions of dollars in lost revenue and resulted in nearly 1000 
arrests 
arnold secretarytreasurer of local 226 said he had heard 
nothing from binions president jack binion since the strike began 
arnold accused binion of trying to break the union at the resort 
we knew it could be a long one and were prepared for it 
arnold said of the walkout 
union officials said 90 percent of the 1100 kitchen workers 
bartenders porters and other union members walked off their jobs 
but an attorney for the horseshoe said half the workers were 
crossing picket lines 
the casino is the first to be struck since union contracts 
expired june 1 
the horseshoe is one of 14 resorts that have not reached new 
pacts with the union but 20 resorts including most major casinos 
along the strip a couple of miles from downtown agreed several 
months ago to fiveyear pacts 
