<TEXT>
phil donahues audience took turns blasting 
general motors corp and filmmaker michael moore on monday as they 
discussed the quirky documentary roger and me 
about 2000 people jammed whiting auditorium for a segment of 
donahues nationally syndicated television show devoted to moores 
film 
the crowd included auto workers who accused gm of sending 
american jobs overseas and flint boosters who said moores movie 
made conditions in flint look worse than they are 
you showed the slummiest areas one woman told moore 
roger and me purports to depict what happened to flint when 
gm shut down factories in the community idling 30000 workers over 
several years 
in the film moore unsuccessfully pursues gm chairman roger 
smith to ask him to come to flint to see what gms layoffs have 
done to the city 
the documentary made for 260000 and released nationwide by 
warner brothers this month has won several awards and is being 
touted as a possible academy award winner for best documentary but 
moore has come under fire by some film critics for misrepresenting 
some time sequences such as the span during which layoffs occurred 
moore a flint native said his movies message was that after 
10 years of reagan and bush its not morning in america for us 
were all working harder for less 
moore said gm has a responsibility to the community where it got 
it started 
the american dream used to be you work hard the company 
prospers you prosper now you work hard the company prospers 
you lose your job he said noting that the layoffs came when gm 
still was making millions a year in profits 
gm critics accused smith of earning millions for himself while 
workers were losing their jobs while roger smith was pocketing 
this money we were standing in line for moldy cheese said one 
woman 
donahue was scheduled to do a single onehour show monday but 
decided to tape a second show immediately after the first because 
many in the crowd had yet to be heard after showing up before dawn 
monday for the 4 pm show 
donahue said gm declined to send anybody to appear with moore 
we are not interested in doing anything that might help 
promote a film that is inaccurate and totally unfair to the city of 
flint and the thousands of dedicated gm employees working there 
according to a gm statement read by donahue 
the company also asked its dealers not to advertise during the 
donahue show about the film donahue said 
moore and many in the audience objected to donahues suggestion 
that gm workers were to blame for the companys loss of market 
share and their jobs 
you made a lot of lousy cars donahue said 
but moore contended the company refused to listen to consumers 
and focused on making cars cheaper 
moore was booed when he admitted to owning a honda civic but 
said that even some socalled americanmade cars are built with 
many foreign made parts 
the show was shown live to about 40 cities and will be shown 
tuesday in more than 150 others 
