<TEXT>
times arent good for the british bobby the 
policeman so admired and respected he never needed to carry a gun 
with disturbing regularity these days his image is being 
tarnished by scandals that range from evidencerigging to falsified 
crimebusting rates 
the scandals have triggered alarm about the integrity of the 
nations 146000member police force and prompted some highly 
public soulsearching by senior officers 
until recently the criticism came chiefly from leftwingers 
whom the police could dismiss as chronic malcontents where corrupt 
officers were exposed they were portrayed as the few bad 
apples in a fundamentally healthy barrel 
britons who follow the police developments closely say it is not 
the level of abuses that has increased but the publics awareness 
of them the criticism is coming increasingly from opinion makers 
who say the bad apple excuse is no longer good enough 
if the publics confidence in the police is lost i cannot see 
how it can be regained columnist bernard levin wrote in the 
times and if it is not regained the damage to our entire way of 
life would be immense so vital is the need for a force which can 
be relied upon 
a public opinion poll published in november indicated the police 
are held in esteem by only 43 percent of britons now in contast to 
83 percent in 1959 
the worst case of what the independent newspaper calls 
institutional rot occurred in october when the court of appeal 
freed four people serving life terms for bombing british pubs 
during a 1974 wave of irish republican army attacks the court 
quashed the conviction of the guildford four after seeing 
evidence that police from the surry county force falsified records 
and lied in court to strengthen their case 
civil libertarians are pressing to reopen other ira convictions 
notably the jailing of six irishmen for a 1974 pub bombing in 
birmingham in central england which killed 21 people the six 
claim they are innocent and were beaten into confessing 
in december a court ordered scotland yard in london to pay a 
record 100000 pounds 165000 in damages to a black man falsely 
accused of carrying illicit drugs it was one of a series of cases 
from 198485 in which police in the notting hill district of west 
london were accused of planting drugs on blacks 
in september investigators found that police in kent had 
increased crimedetection rates by pressing convicted prisoners to 
confess falsely to extra crimes it led to the dismissal of a 
detective sergeant and heavy fines for six of his colleagues 
public opinion was further inflamed by news that the policeman 
who exposed the corruption was being coldshouldered by his 
colleagues and was threatened with dismissal when he demanded a 
transfer 
the british force is divided into 52 constabularies mostly on 
county lines and usually officers from one county are called in to 
investigate suspected abuses by another 
commented the independent at the moment with half a dozen of 
our major forces investigating one another the police are in 
danger of running out of investigators to investigate the 
investigators 
signs of a dramatic new approach came in august when chief 
constable geoffrey dear of the west midlands force took the unusual 
step of dismantling his entire seriouscrime squad over allegations 
of fabricated confessions and doctored evidence more than 50 
officers were sidelined 
dear got what appeared to be crucial backing a month later from 
sir peter imbert commissioner of scotland yard in a watershed 
speech to a police conference 
sometimes it must seem that we set out deliberately to 
frustrate the inquirer and in doing so we manage to turn a 
grievance into a crusade he said police reticence he added 
carried quiet but strong implications of corruption 
the scope of abuses is expected to narrow sharply with the new 
police and criminal evidence act which requires interrogators to 
record every word said in the room and hold no one for more than 36 
hours without court authorization and access to a lawyer by 1991 
all interrogations will have to be taperecorded 
that law already has led to hundreds of detectives requesting 
transfers on grounds that they could not cope with the exacting new 
procedures said barry irving director of the police foundation 
an independent research group 
scotland yards imbert urges more emphasis on oldstyle policing 
based on close consultation with local communities especially 
ethnic groups 
the public have a right to be actively involved in determining 
how policing is developed he said in his september speech 
paj waddington a reading university expert on police says 
that policing is inherently scandalprone what seems to vary is 
the extent to which people perceive problems as being scandals 
waddington said in an interview that police malpractice is 
substantially less than at any time in our history and the 
fact that police violence still makes headlines demonstrates that 
it is still regarded as an unusual phenomenon 
but in recent times the old image of the friendly neighborhood 
bobby has been supplanted by a new breed hardened by innercity 
riots in the early 1980s and frequent picket line violence 
criminologist robert reiner of the london school of economics 
thinks the accumulation of gross abuses is extremely disturbing 
but i dont think its a sign the police have gone bad 
the police are doing their job as they always did he said in an 
interview the difference is that the public perception of them has 
changed 
there is a crisis in the public legitimacy of the british 
police he said 
</TEXT>
