<TEXT>
once an economic power that drew ships from 
around the world to its piers at the head of the chesapeake bay 
the port of baltimore is losing ground to its competitors and its 
reputation for labor troubles 
even the unexpectedly quick settlement of a threeday 
dockworkers strike last week failed to appreciably brighten 
prospects for the 1 billion complex 
even a threeday walkout has reverberations its like the 
shot heard round the world baltimore goes out again said state 
delegate eileen rehrmann it sends a message all over the world 
that were unreliable 
the jan 19 strike by about 2000 members of the international 
longshoremens association stranded cargo containers on piers and 
prompted about a dozen vessels to divert to competing waterfronts 
officials said 
the dockworkers who struck over jurisdiction of clerical jobs 
went back to work tuesday and ratified a new contract that gave up 
60 of those jobs 
yet it may be more significant that the union gave up its rain 
clause a local work rule blamed for higher labor costs the new 
contract lets managers instead of the union decide when weather 
is too hazardous to work 
us rep helen bentley rmd who acted as a mediator in the 
contract dispute said eliminating the rain clause alone would save 
steamship lines about 25 million a year 
the damage has already been done internationally and within 
our own state said gov william donald schaefer who had 
threatened a state takeover of the ports operations long before 
last weeks strike 
schaefer returned from european and middle east trade missions 
last year complaining about the ports labor image abroad and for 
years has complained of lagging modernization to keep up with the 
boom in containerized shipping 
richard hughes head of the ila local representing clerical 
workers contends that the port should control its administrative 
costs eliminating such things as executive bonuses and make its 
rates more competitive with regional competitors 
hughes whose jurisdictional complaint led to the threeday 
strike said he doesnt consider the contract satisfactory raising 
the possibility of another wrangle when the pact expires in 
november 
ila district president horace alston who heads the five ila 
locals working in the port of baltimore didnt return a phone call 
baltimore a 12hour sail up the bay from the atlantic ocean 
once was insulated from hard times by its position as the harbor 
closest to the nations industrial heartland 
freight deregulation in the 1970s turned that into a liability 
with customers shopping for competitive truck and rail rates from 
ports that huge steamships could reach more conveniently 
in the mid1980s the port authority began to step into labor 
negotiations between the ila and dock employers represented by the 
steamship trade association 
port officials were anxious to obtain union concessions to 
improve the ports reputation for reliability and lower its costs 
but that only strained relations between the ila and the employers 
who lease the docks and hire from the labor pool 
richard trainor head of the maryland port commission said the 
economic effect of the strike goes far beyond the 2000 or so ila 
members 
he estimated that 30000 to 40000 people make a living from the 
ports business even that is far less than what used to be ten 
years ago a state study found the port directly or indirectly 
supported more than 100000 people 
port of baltimore officials say 28 ship lines have folded 
merged or deserted baltimore in the past five years 
while shipping volume has declined worldwide baltimores market 
share has been sapped by other atlantic seaboard ports especially 
virginias hampton roads complex at norfolk 
port of baltimore figures show that between 1982 and 1988 its 
share of midwestbound freight dwindled from 18 percent to 10 
percent while norfolks climbed from 6 percent to 9 percent 
baltimores midatlantic share went from 30 percent to 20 
percent while norfolks rose from 13 percent to 18 percent 
the sun in baltimore reported thursday that last year for the 
first time virginia ports probably surpassed baltimore in the 
amount of general cargo handled 
maryland port officials said their 1989 numbers werent yet 
prepared for publication but figures through september show a 64 
percent drop in general cargo from the year before 
trainor said the port must become more financially attractive to 
shippers 
if youre in business selling something for 1 and everybody 
else is selling it for 50 cents you might as well make up your 
mind youre in the wrong business because the public is going to 
make it up for you he said 
</TEXT>
