<TEXT>
president mikhail s gorbachevs decision to send 
troops to quell the azerbaijanarmenian conflict has dragged native 
russians into the conflict throwing a volatile new ingredient into 
a simmering ethnic stew 
both armenians and azerbaijanis now accuse gorbachev and the 
russiandominated kremlin leadership of letting the 2yearold 
battle over the disputed nagornokarabakh region slip out of 
control 
the decision on jan 19 to send soldiers to crush armed 
nationalists in baku the azerbaijani capital has focused 
resentment on slavic soldiers their dependents and russians who 
live in the region 
while gorbachev pleaded for a united soviet union to help solve 
the caucasus dilemma russian mothers were telling him they were 
not interested in risking their sons lives to stop the killing in 
their view the armenianazerbaijani dispute was more like the 
unpopular war in afghanistan than an issue of internal security 
major gen sergei kupreyev a member of the special commission 
from moscow administering nagornokarabakh complained in the jan 
23 issue of the weekly new times magazine that neither armenians 
nor azerbaijanis wanted to compromise 
no reasonable words are accepted now he said we are 
doing everything we can to talk our informal leaders into starting 
negotiations but the war is going on and our efforts are all in 
vain 
the military move intended to restore order in baku after 
azerbaijanis began attacking and killing the minority armenians 
united azerbaijanis against moscow 
the azerbaijan government demanded withdrawal of the soviet 
soldiers and an end to the state of emergency it threatened to 
secede from the soviet union never before had it so openly defied 
moscow 
most of the republic went on strike in protest 
in an area where the truth often is obscured by a maddening 
blurring of the facts the number of people killed by the military 
was a source of exaggeration 
comrades in baku more than 9000 people were killed read 
one sign carried by two young men in a march in moscow the day that 
the dead actually were being buried in baku but in the azerbaijani 
capital there were not 9000 graves there were 119 and that 
figure was higher than that offered by official sources which put 
the toll at 83 including 14 servicemen and members of their 
families 
baku journalist shain hadjiev said most of the soldiers sent 
into baku appeared to be russians posters declaring gorbachev 
the butcher of the azerbaijani people were displayed during 
rallies in baku he said 
in a period of high ethnic awareness spurred by gorbachevs 
reforms russians now are regarded by some in republics such as the 
baltics and moldavia as unwelcome colonizers 
until now they had managed to stay out of direct involvement in 
the conflict between armenians and azerbaijanis 
but world chess champion garri kasparov a jewisharmenian 
native of azerbaijan who got 60 of his friends and relatives out of 
baku during the ethnic violence told a moscow news conference that 
the conflict in baku could envelope the russian population 
if clashes are provoked between russians and azerbaijanis and 
if there are victims or refugees among the russian population just 
think what might happen if they show up in moscow he told a news 
conference 
it was unclear how many of the victims in baku were family 
members of servicemen but soviet officials took the threat 
seriously by wednesday more than 16000 dependents had been 
evacuated 
officials reported that the evacuation program was suspended 
thursday because of assurances from the azerbaijan peoples front 
that dependents no longer were in danger 
the labor newspaper trud reported attacks on the homes of some 
of bakus 100000 russians and said azerbaijanis were refusing to 
sell food to russians the interfax news service a publication of 
the official radio moscow said antirussian and antimilitary 
speeches were being made at rallies in many azerbaijani cities 
russian parents were having none of gorbachevs appeals the 
flashpoint was a decision to call up reserves on russian territory 
north of the caucasus mountains to help restore order in armenia 
and azerbaijan 
i wont give up my son a woman shouted in film broadcast 
nationwide by soviet tv from stavropol gorbachevs political power 
base we put up with everything we put up with it we put up 
with it how long are we going to put up with everything 
we dont want the peoples of these republics to call us 
occupants we dont want another afghanistan said another 
faced with such ire the kremlin unceremoniously backed down 
kupreyev noted that the bitter experience in afghanistan and 
gorbachevs opening of soviet society had affected soldiers 
attitudes 
soldiers dont want to die in domestic ethnic clashes he 
said there is some displeasure among the troops 
</TEXT>
