<TEXT>
gerard f scannell shudders when he recalls 
the amputations that some pharmaceutical workers suffered before he 
instituted safety reforms at johnson amp johnson plants worldwide 
as the head of the occupational safety and health 
administration hes banking on the conviction that corporate 
executives share that feeling 
but as a former executive himself he believes compassion can be 
bolstered by the bottom line safety expenditures save money in the 
long run 
he draws the conclusion from 11 years directing corporate safety 
for the new brunswick njbased drug giant where workplace 
injuries dropped more than 90 percent during his tenure 
i made money for them he says safety does pay 
at the labor department scannell began translating some of that 
corporatemindedness to safeguarding the nations workplaces even 
before his october confirmation 
my plan is to get to those ceos he says i was on the 
firing line out there in industry i think i know what im talking 
about and i think people know that its not going to be easy for 
people to bluff me 
health threats abound in office and factory air in dangerous 
machinery on construction sites in stresses and strains from 
unnatural movements scannell is worried about repetitive strain 
injuries in everything from the wrists of word processing typists 
to the arms of meatpackers 
he hopes to begin attacking the latter class of problems by 
releasing ergonomic guidelines for the red meat industry in 
february 
his agency also is battling dentists who argue they cannot 
afford to meet proposed standards to protect health workers from 
bloodborne pathogens that cause hepatitis and aids scannell hopes 
to get those standards in place by years end 
scannell 54 has hopscotched between jobs in government and 
industry including safety posts with aetna casualty amp surety co 
thiokol chemical corp and rohm amp haas co and a stint at osha 
from 1971 to 1979 he has shown a willingness to confront possible 
detractors by seeking out labor leaders industry officials 
academics doctors anyone who will listen 
one of the adversaries he faced is safety gadfly joseph kinney 
executive director of the nonprofit national safe workplace 
institute in chicago 
scannell is deeply committed to making progress kinney said 
in a telephone interview he came here twice it was kind of a 
surprise when he called us i said are you sure youve got the 
right organization 
after all kinney says government had not previously 
appreciated his groups work the reagan administration hated us 
passionately 
kinney is waiting to see whether scannell continues slapping 
companies with large fines such as the 73 million against usx 
corp last november for alleged safety recordkeeping and health 
violations 
but scannell prides himself most on being a negotiator who can 
elicit voluntary compliance from a company rather than collect a 
stiff fine while bad practices continue 
if i can get better protection for workers by lowering 
penalties im going to do it im going to extract more out of you 
in promises than i can probably legally cite you for scannell 
says i want more than what the standards require 
those who know scannell say that as the first person to 
dismantle a live sidewinder missile back in the late 1950s he did 
so as a navy explosives expert he knows what safety means 
but others worry he will be hamstrung by the office of 
management and budget 
