<TEXT>
agriculture department scientists say many 
farm crops show good resistance to acid rain and that there is a 
possibility of developing even tougher strains 
a team at the agricultural research services laboratory in 
raleigh nc exposed 216 varieties of 18 crops to simulated acid 
rain many times more acidic than found now in the eastern united 
states 
the simulated acid rain caused no significant injury nor did 
it reduce growth in most species the agency said in a report 
acid rain contains pollutants from the atmosphere such as 
sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide present in exhausts from factory 
smokestacks and automobiles these chemicals make the rain more 
acid 
the experiments were conducted by botanist denis t dubay plant 
pathologist allen s heagle and plant physiologist walter w heck 
tomatoes eggplant snapbeans cotton peanuts and soybeans 
were the only crops whose leaves showed damage of more than 5 
percent after the onehour exposure the report said the most 
sensitive variety of tomato had as much as 24 percent of its leaf 
area damaged by the single exposure 
but at the other end of the scale potatoes corn lettuce 
winter wheat orchardgrass melons fescue cucumbers alfalfa 
clover and squash all had less than 2 percent leaf damage 
crops that suffered the greatest damage in the shorterterm 
acute tests also registered the most damage in chronic tests for up 
to 15 days of simulated acid rain at a time 
leaf damage varied greatly by varieties for tomatoes and 
soybeans raising the possibility of breeding hardier strains of 
acidresistant crops if those are needed someday the report said 
</TEXT>
