<TEXT>
a pilot of older jetliners says fuel gauges on 
airplanes like the boeing 707 that crashed on new yorks long 
island are not highly accurate especially when tanks are low and 
fuel is sloshing around 
you could not trust them below 10000 pounds of fuel said 
john nance a former braniff pilot nance who lives in tacoma is 
an airline safety analyst 
the national transportation safety board which is investigating 
the crash has said gauges recovered from the wreckage of the 
23yearold plane indicate the plane had about 10000 pounds of 
fuel perhaps enough to keep it aloft the 15 miles from the crash 
site to its destination john f kennedy international airport 
investigators caution however that the fuel estimate could be 
wrong 
the avianca airliner crashed thursday night in the affluent 
community of cove neck ny killing 73 people and injuring 85 
because of the absence of engine noise before the crash the lack 
of fuel odor and the lack of fire after the crash investigators 
focused from the start on the possibility the airliner ran out of 
fuel 
nance said that with small amounts of fuel on older jetliners 
including the 707 and the mcdonnell douglas dc8 gauges reading 
the fuel splashing around in the several tanks were all over the 
map you really dont know what youve got 
he said that to burn under 10000 pounds is a dangerous 
procedure to burn below 5000 is an emergency 
boeing officials have said they dont know of any problems with 
fuel gauges on 707 airliners few of which are still in use by 
united states airlines 
spokesman jack gamble said sunday that each airline provides its 
own flight manuals to pilots for instruction on methods to check 
fuel levels 
airplane manufacturers are required to calibrate gauges before 
delivering planes he said after that however the worthiness of 
the gauges is up to the airlines and federal regulators 
nance who still flies as a heavy jet commander with the air 
force reserve said he never flew in boeing 707s but did pilot 
dc8s which have similar fuel gauges 
while the gauges lack accuracy he said the equipment 
represented the known technology at the time the planes were built 
beginning in the 1950s newergeneration jetliners he said have 
much more accurate fuel gauges 
on the older dc8s the gauges were so unreliable that we 
were directed by braniff to disregard them totally and keep a 
fuelburn chart he said 
jetliners are equipped with fuelflow gauges that measure the 
amount of fuel being burned at any given time he said and a 
flight engineers job includes keeping track of fuel flow and fuel 
used 
i would always want to make sure that i started a flight 
with a known quantity and keep track of the fuel burn i would 
never depend just on the fuel gauges he said 
he said 707 flight crews are aware of the systems limitations 
and become familiar with each airplanes idiosyncrasies he noted 
that avianca has been flying the 707 for some time and its staff 
would presumably know the aircraft he said any number of scenarios 
could have taken place thursday evening but that the crew might 
not have looked at the instruments might have seen the wrong 
indications on the gauges and believed them or might have 
misinterpreted the gauges the crew told controllers the plane was 
low on fuel but did not formally declare a fuel emergency 
nance cited the case of a united air lines flight into portland 
ore in december 1978 the dc8 ran out of fuel and crashed 
though the gauges indicated the plane had 4000 pounds of fuel 
left fewer than a dozen died 
