<TEXT>
the budget president bush sent congress today 
includes a new attempt to encourage family savings and a 
significant boost for head start while making a fresh effort to 
dramatically shift the focus of federal housing programs 
the 123 trillion fiscal 1991 budget proposal also includes a 
major cash infusion for the war on drugs and new initiatives in 
the form of higher spending for space and biotechnology programs 
other programs slated for significant spending increases are the 
federal aviation administration a proposal that relies heavily on 
dipping into an aviation trust fund and efforts to clean up 
hazardous materials at nuclear plants and other facilities run by 
the federal government 
some of the initiatives offered in the spending blueprint 
are indeed new others like the presidents childcare and 
capitalgains proposals are simply new attempts to win 
congressional approval of bush proposals that did not survive 
congress last year 
and for all its new and reworked initiatives the budget 
proposal also includes an attempt to head off one of the biggest 
initiatives likely to emerge on capitol hill an attempt to take 
advantage of the socalled peace dividend created by declining 
world tensions by spending money now earmarked for the military on 
domestic programs 
the sum of all such planned expenditures totals about 10 times 
the overestimated dividend which is itself perhaps five times the 
actual dividend budget director richard darman said in a message 
accompanying the budget thus washington entertains the notion 
of spending 50 times a dividend that has not definitively 
materialized a true wonderland phenomenon 
the battle over the real or imagined peace dividend is 
likely to be the biggest budget skirmish several of the 
presidents other initiatives also appear certain to alienate 
congress majority democrats while others likely will be accepted 
quickly perhaps with tinkering 
here are brief summaries of several bush policy initiatives the 
numbers are for proposed fiscal 1991 spending unless labeled as 
spending authority meaning that the amount shown is what the 
administration is asking to spend spent over several years 
family savings accounts in a bid to improve the nations 
anemic savings rate bush proposes exempting from income tax the 
interest paid on family savings accounts that are held for seven 
years the limit would be 5000 for those filing a joint tax 
return 2500 for individual returns withdrawals taken after the 
seven years would be tax free and a 10 percent excise penalty would 
be assessed on early withdrawals 
head start bush proposes adding 500 million in spending 
authority to the preschool education program in fiscal 1991 for a 
total of 19 billion the 36 percent increase should allow the 
program a favorite of democrats and republicans alike to enroll 
180000 more 4yearolds from lowincome families according to the 
administration about 450000 children now participate in head 
start programs 
housing the presidents 23 billion department of housing and 
urban development budget includes expansion of two of the pet 
projects of hud secretary jack kemp urban enterprise zones and 
tenant ownership bushs proposal to shift nearly 60 million from 
lowincome rental programs to a certificate program that allows 
tenants of housing projects and other federally subsidized housing 
programs to buy their units likely will face stiff opposition in 
congress from liberal democrats who do not believe tenant ownership 
will work on a large scale in many areas of the country 
the drug war bush unveiled this part of his budget last week 
proposing to boost federal spending authority for the drug war by 
11 billion to 106 billion 
space bush proposes increasing the national aeronautics and 
space administrations spending from 12 billion to 141 billion 
the budget projects a record 10 space shuttle flights next fiscal 
year at a cost of more than 8 billion and also proposes budget 
authority of 26 billion for development of the manned space 
station and 12 billion for exploration activities to support the 
planned moonmars mission 
air traffic control bush proposed an increase in overall faa 
spending that would see a reduction in the amount of direct federal 
spending for air safety while the amount taken from an aviation 
trust fund financed by user fees would increase sharply 
bush proposed outlays of 12 billion in federal funds for the 
faa next year down from about 3 billion in the current fiscal 
year while spending 6 billion from the trust fund up from 34 
billion this year bush said his proposed increase for the faa 
would allow for the hiring of 495 more air traffic controllers and 
300 safety specialists the administration said those increases 
were needed because of increasing number of commercial flights and 
the aging of the nations aircraft fleet bush proposed increased 
user fees to help pay for the increase 
hazardous cleanup bush proposes spending 42 billion to clean 
up hazardous materials at department of energy nuclear plants and 
other facilities run by nasa and the departments of defense 
interior agriculture and transportation that would be an increase 
642 million over the current fiscal year 
</TEXT>
