<TEXT>
how do you explain a 123 trillion federal 
budget with a deficit in the billions of dollars tucked away in 
nearly 190000 accounts and recorded in a book that runs to 1569 
intimidating pages 
budget director richard g darman used childs terms today to 
tell readers what it all means in an introduction to president 
bushs fiscal 1991 budget plan darman spoke solemnly of pacmen 
the cookie monster and wonderland 
to darman the federal budget might be seen as the ultimate 
cookie monster a reference to the gruff character on the 
sesame street childrens tv show who cannot resist gobbling 
up anything and everything that might be consumed especially 
cookies 
the budgets excessive tendencies toward consumption are not 
exactly ennobling darman wrote but at the same time its 
underlying motivation is clearly not malevolent 
what harm it may cause is largely unintended its massive 
presence might be understood as little more than a compilation of 
cookies received cookies crumbled and crumbs spewed forth 
darman says the cookie monster analogy isnt fair to the cookie 
monster or the budget in reality a budget is not just a 
monstrous mass of cookies and crumbs he says it is more an 
implicit statement of values and expectations for the future 
using the imagery of the pacman video game darman warns of 
rising costs of such federal liabilities as health care pensions 
mandatory benefit programs insurance coverage and environmental 
cleanup obligations 
each is like a hidden pacman waiting to spring forward and 
consume another line of resource dots in the budget maze the 
budget chief wrote 
then its off to wonderland darmans name for a political 
fairyland where he believes congress is heading when it starts 
tinkering with the budget 
darman says a new game on capitol hill is finding ways to spend 
the peace dividend the supposed savings in defense spending 
resulting from the recent easing of eastwest tensions 
it starts by overestimating the dividend he wrote then 
each player plans to spend the dividend in his or her preferred 
way the sum of all such planned expenditures totals about 10 times 
the overestimated dividend which is itself perhaps five times the 
actual dividend 
thus washington entertains the notion of spending 50 times a 
dividend that has not yet definitively materialized a true 
wonderland phenomenon darman says 
he also characterizes as a very dangerous game politically 
the recent congressional demands for a cut in social security taxes 
indeed wonderland seems to be running wild with attractive 
fantasies but without yet having established coherent direction 
he wrote 
in a footnote darman observed that the budget document was 
published this year in a single volume rather than the seven 
separate budget books issued in previous years 
the aim he said was to make the federal budget easier and 
perhaps more informative to read 
there is no formal record of the number of individuals who may 
have read covertocover the previous sevenvolume editions of 
the budget darman wrote nor are there epidemiological studies 
of their fate 
</TEXT>
