<TEXT>
angolan guerrilla leader jonas savimbi 
today said pressure from the superpowers and angolas weariness 
with bloodshed would bring an end to the 15yearold civil war this 
year 
savimbi made the comments on his first visit to lisbon since 
portugal granted independence to the african nation in 1975 when 
fighting began between his usbacked guerrillas and the marxist 
government supported by the soviet union and cuba 
portugal recognizes the existing government and savimbi had been 
banned until this year from coming to the country 
the pressure for peace from inside and outside angola will be 
so great i dont see how either side will be able to continue 
fighting in 1990 he said we are going to launch an enormous 
effort to end the war this year 
savimbis remarks came against a background of increased 
diplomatic efforts to break a deadlock in the angolan peace process 
as us envoy herman cohen traveled from angola to london where he 
was reportedly to hold talks with soviet officials on the war in 
angola 
a ceasefire agreement was signed in june in gbadolite zaire 
but it collapsed within days 
since december the guerrillas have been holding off what they 
describe as the biggest government offensive ever mounted against 
their strongholds 
savimbi also said the guerrilla group was involved in direct 
contacts with cuba to provide guarantees that his forces would not 
attack cuban soldiers cuba suspended the withdrawal of its troops 
from angola after four cubans where killed in a guerrilla raid jan 
21 
savimbi described the attack as involuntary and said the 
guerrilla group would provide cuba with assurances such incidents 
would not be repeated 
cuba began withdrawing its troops after south africa pledged in 
december 1988 to halt aid to the guerrillas and grant independence 
to neighboring nambia 
savimbi said the next step in the peace process should be a halt 
in the government offensive followed by moves to bring about direct 
talks between himself and eduardo dos santos 
the americans and the portuguese can play a more active role 
in the search for peace by establishing where the common ground 
between the two sides lies and using that to bring us together 
savimbi said 
he said washington and lisbon should act in support of peace 
efforts by president mobuto sese seko of zaire 
savimbi said the guerrillas backed mobuto as a mediator and 
cohen the us assistant secretary of state for african affairs 
had told him by telephone today that angolan president jose eduardo 
dos santos shared the same position 
the guerrilla leader was on the third day of a visit that marked 
the end of a 15year ban on his travel to portugal 
