<TEXT>
east germanys communists agreed to share 
power with the opposition and move up elections by nearly two 
months because of growing civil unrest that threatens the countrys 
existence premier hans modrow said today 
the government said it would hold elections on march 18 instead 
of may 6 and form a governing coalition with the opposition until 
a freely elected leadership takes office 
also today authorities arrested former hardline leader erich 
honecker and a prosecutor said he would be tried for high treason 
in march 
chief prosecutor hansjuergen joseph told parliament that 
honecker and former politburo members erich mielke guenter mittag 
and joachim herrmann would be tried by the supreme court all four 
have been expelled from the party 
if convicted honecker who was ousted nov 10 in east germanys 
peaceful revolt against his 18year stalinist regime could face 
life in prison 
honecker 77 was taken to prison after being released from a 
hospital where he had undergone surgery for kidney cancer the 
official adn news agency said his lawyer wolfgang vogel asked 
prosecutors to free honecker from custody because he is too ill to 
stay in jail adn said 
in bonn west german chancellor helmut kohl today said he plans 
to make campaign appearances for conservatives running in the east 
german elections kohl a christian democrat said he will be 
talking this week with prodemocracy opposition forces and east 
germanys christian democratic leaders to decide which party to 
back 
opposition activists initially had resisted overtures by the 
stilldominant communists to join an interim government but 
apparently felt the situation had become so dire that they had no 
other choice 
east germanys economy is on the brink of disaster and many of 
its most promising young workers have joined a destabilizing exodus 
to the west as many as 2500 east germans have been fleeing daily 
modrow urged parliament today to support the agreement with the 
opposition 
the premier said strikes and the exodus of workers have worsened 
the economy and set off a chain reaction of economic breakdowns 
threatening the existence of east germany 
modrow said bomb threats and vandalism have spread protection 
of citizens can no longer be fully guaranteed modrow told the 
500member peoples chamber 
the current government coalition is proving increasingly 
fragile modrow said economic and social tensions have 
increased the economic situation is deteriorating in a worrying 
way 
opposition forces had wanted to stay out of the government until 
the elections to avoid sharing blame for the countrys economic 
catastrophe 
but modrows transition government a collection of relatively 
reformist communists who are trying to salvage their standing among 
the citizenry was beginning to unravel reforms to encourage 
western investment have been held up by disputes between communists 
and various opposition groups 
as a result a decline in production and living standards has 
hastened 
seeking to draw opposition leaders into a grand coalition to 
govern until the elections modrow opened talks sunday with 
representatives of nine reform movements and a handful of minor 
parties long aligned with the communists 
the communists suffered the defections of some leading reformers 
a week ago and the crisis deepened thursday when three ministers 
from the christian democratic union a party traditionally allied 
with the communists pulled out of the 27member cabinet 
modrow and more than 40 representatives of rival political 
forces agreed that a new cabinet will be submitted by wednesday to 
parliament 
the decisions were announced by martin ziegler a lutheran 
church official who said the new leadership would include one 
member from each of the nine opposition groups represented at 
weekly talks with government 
he said the ministers would be named without portfolio and it 
was not immediately clear if the cabinet would be expanded or if 
some current ministers would give up seats the government 
currently has 16 communist ministers 
wolfgang schnur of the opposition democratic awakening said the 
cabinet members will decide later how to distribute ministerial 
responsibilities 
all the political groups are vying for voter support in this 
country of 16 million 
many opposition parties held weekend congresses to chart 
election strategy but the meetings served more to highlight 
differences dividing the groups and preventing the emergence of a 
united force to challenge the communists 
new forum the largest of the prodemocracy groups previously 
claimed 200000 members but a moderate faction split off from the 
movement to form the german forum party over the weekend 
meanwhile christian democratic union leader lothar de maiziere 
announced he was prepared to seek an election coalition with 
democratic awakening and the german social union two east german 
opposition groups that support marketoriented reforms and closer 
ties with west germany 
