<TEXT>
the new nambian legislature today 
proposed that the territory declare independence march 21 and bring 
to an end 75 years of south african rule 
the constituent assembly submitted the date to namibias south 
african administrator louis pienaar who is expected to approve 
the assembly plans to vote on the proposal at a session tuesday 
south africa has agreed to grant independence to namibia 
africas last colony under a regional peace treaty more than 
6000 united nations military and civilian personnel have been 
supervising the process since last april 
the 72member constituent assembly elected in november also is 
debating a democratic westernstyle constitution and is to begin 
voting on the document tuesday articlebyarticle 
all leading parties represented in the assembly have expressed 
support for the proposed constitution and no major disagreements 
are expected 
the document has a declaration of fundamental rights including 
freedom of movement speech and a free press it also envisions a 
multiparty democracy regular elections an independent judiciary 
and an executive president limited to two fiveyear terms 
one potentially contentious provision would allow for detention 
without trial at times of war and during a state of emergency at 
such times the government could detain a person without charge if 
he was considered a clear and present danger to the security of 
the state 
the leftist southwest africa peoples organization which waged 
a 23year bush war against south african rule captured 41 seats in 
the assembly and will form the first government the groups 
leader sam nujoma is expected to become the countrys first 
president 
however at least 48 assembly members or twothirds must 
approve each article of the constitution 
the democratic turnhalle alliance a multiracial coalition that 
favors a free enterprise economy has 21 seats the 10 remaining 
assembly seats are divided among five parties 
