<TEXT>
the trial of joseph hazelwood got under 
way today with the judge predicting it would take a fairly long 
time to select a jury to weigh the charges against the former 
tanker captain in the nations worst oil spill 
superior court judge karl johnstone spent much of the morning 
briefing reporters on courtroom rules in the highly publicized case 
hazelwood 43 faces a felony charge of criminal mischief and 
misdemeanor charges of operating a vessel while intoxicated 
reckless endangerment and negligent discharge of oil he was the 
captain of the exxon valdez when the tanker ran aground march 24 
spilling 11 million gallons of crude oil 
johnstone said jury selection in the case would not begin until 
tuesday and that he would spend the rest of today on pretrial 
motions in motions similar to ones that have been rejected in the 
past hazelwoods lawyers are seeking again to have his failed 
sobriety test prohibited as evidence and challenging the states 
jurisdiction in the case 
i expect jury selection will take a fairly long time 
johnstone said estimating it could take two weeks 
about 90 prospective jurors have been given standard threepage 
questionnaires and about 30 a day will be questioned the judge 
said a larger number will be screened if a panel of 12 plus 
alternates cannot be found from the pool of 90 people 
johnstone said he expects each side in the case to spend about 
three weeks presenting arguments 
largely for reasons of fairness the trial was moved here from 
valdez the port where the exxon valdez took on its cargo of north 
slope crude hours before the tanker struck charted bligh reef 
before he left his home state of new york to come here to face 
trial hazelwood said said he looked forward to arguing that the 
spill was a tragic accident not a criminal act 
id like to get rid of the misconception that i got drunk ran 
the ship aground and just shrugged my shoulders and walked away 
because thats just not what happened hazelwood said in an 
interview with the associated press last week in his new york 
lawyers office 
hazelwood who was not on the bridge when the accident occurred 
failed a bloodalcohol test 10 hours after the exxon valdez struck 
bligh reef in prince william sound 
the spill killed thousands of animals and disrupted commercial 
fishing seasons exxon says the cleanup has cost 2 billion 
the charges carry combined penalties of up to seven years three 
months in prison and 61000 in fines 
defense attorney dick madson planned to argue that hazelwood 
left clear instructions for the crew and cannot be held criminally 
responsible for their actions third mate gregory cousins was at 
the wheel of the 987foot vessel when it ran aground after leaving 
designated shipping lanes 
cousins was expected to testify he was served with a subpoena 
in tampa fla on friday at the request of assistant district 
attorney brent cole the hazelwood prosecutor 
cole alleged that cousins was not licensed to navigate in prince 
william sound cousins declined to comment before the trial 
in an affidavit cole also alleged that hazelwood was seen 
drinking at two bars within three hours before his ship left the 
port of valdez 
other witnesses madson said he will call include other crew 
members and an expert who will describe a computer simulation of 
the ships course and testify that the exxon valdez would have 
cleared bligh reef had the crew followed hazelwoods instructions 
the trial originally scheduled for october in valdez was 
delayed as courts dealt with reassigning judges processing thick 
legal motions and other matters 
the trial was moved to anchorage on grounds a fair proceeding 
could not be obtained in valdez and because alaskas largest city 
has a substantial jury pool and facilities for news media 
hazelwood was expected to be in the courtroom throughout the 
trial 
since being fired the seaman from huntington ny has been 
working as a lobsterman before his tanker ran aground the longest 
he had been ashore since he was an adolescent was two or three 
months 
i get stark crazy when i am too far from the salt water he 
said chainsmoking during the interview 
hazelwood said he was confident that once alaskans heard the 
case against him they will agree that this was a tragic accident 
nothing more 
