<TEXT>
president bush proposed monday to trim federal 
transportation outlays next year to 78 billion but to hire more 
employees to handle growing air traffic congestion and detect 
safety problems in aging airliners 
bushs proposed budget for fiscal 1991 which starts oct 1 
calls for a 264 million increase in funds for the federal aviation 
administration a 7 percent boost to 41 billion for the agency 
the higher funds would enable the faa to hire nearly 500 new air 
traffic controllers 300 new safety inspectors and additional 
security specialists there were 16921 controllers on the federal 
payroll as of dec 31 
additional staff are needed because of projected increases in 
aviation activity and because of the aging of the aircraft fleet 
the faa said 
the staffing increases will result in the largest air traffic 
control work force in the history of the faa and more than double 
the staff devoted to detecting the problems of aging aircraft 
the agency said 
the announcement came as federal investigators were exploring an 
apparent communications mixup between regional and local new york 
air traffic controllers in the crash of a colombian avianca 
jetliner on long island last thursday killing 73 people and 
injuring 85 others the plane which was low on fuel was trying to 
land at kennedy international airport 
overall bush urged reducing transportation department outlays 
from the current 92 million to 78 billion next year and 
putting greater reliance on taxsupported highway and aviation 
trust funds and publicprivate enterprises to finance major 
transportation improvements 
the trust funds are supported by a variety of user fees and 
excise taxes on such items as gasoline when they are taken into 
account total transportation spending would rise to 287 billion 
in fiscal 1991 compared with 282 billion this year 
other bush proposals included 
a ticket tax or surcharge on departing air passengers to help 
finance airport construction and improvements 
a fivefold increase in research spending on developing 
socalled smart cars and smart highways using stateofthe art 
electronics communications and computer technology to improve 
traffic control systems that warn drivers of dangerous situations 
and make more efficient use of the existing road system 
10 million to assess the potential of a publicprivate system 
of nonpolluting highspeed trains guided by magnets and achieving 
maximum speeds of 300 miles per hour 
the administration proposed a 12 percent increase from 65 
billion to 72 billion in programs to benefit air travelers as 
part of a longterm plan to modernize aviation facilities expand 
airport capacity and bolster aviation research and development 
the request for 190 million earmarked for research and 
development a 12 percent boost in current spending would 
finance a study of metal fatigue and corrosion in older aircraft 
and a new laboratory to perfect airport detection of explosive 
devices in luggage 
it also would pay for development of new ways to prevent 
aircraft fires and minimize fire injuries 
bush proposed cutting off operating subsidies to mass transit 
systems in cities with populations of 1 million or more saying the 
federal contribution represents less than 6 percent of those 
budgets 
