<TEXT>
a program aimed at bringing the peregrine falcon 
back from the brink of extinction in illinois has reached its goal 
a decade earlier than expected the project director said monday 
when the chicago peregrine release program ends this summer 46 
of the crowsized birds of prey will have been reintroduced into 
illinois said director vicki byre 
before the program began in 1986 peregrines had not been seen 
in illinois for 35 years wiped out by pesticides that damaged 
their ability to reproduce ms byre said in a telephone interview 
by the end of 1960s peregrines were entirely extinct east of 
the rocky mountains she said 
but with the help of projects nationwide there are now likely 
more than 100 breeding pairs east of the rockies and probably 
more than that west of the rockies she said peregrines in the 
western united states have fared better because there is less 
cropland and thus less pesticide use ms byre said 
its because of man that they have disappeared so i think we 
owe it to our fellow living creatures to help them back she said 
changes have been made since the neardemise of the peregrine 
natures fastest bird and known for making spectacular swoops at 
200 mph to catch its prey smaller birds in flight 
the pesticide ddt was banned in this country in 1972 and the 
federal government declared the falcon an endangered species the 
following year 
the peregrines natural habitat mostly wide open cliffs also 
has changed places where it once roosted have been populated with 
homes trees and the falcons most deadly predator the great 
horned owl said carl becker chief of the illinois department of 
conservations division of natural heritage 
so most projects like chicagos release the birds into urban 
wilds ornithologists have discovered the lofty ledges of 
skyscrapers make ideal homes 
under the chicago program coordinated by the chicago academy of 
sciences and the conservation department 5weekold peregrine 
chicks raised in captivity are released in groups of about five and 
provided with food until they can thrive on their own each bird 
costs 1750 
the whole thing that we measure the success of the program by 
is not just if you can get them released in the wild but if they 
can mate on their own ms byre said 
so far peregrines in illinois have produced at least six young 
she said 
our goal was to try to get three breeding pairs into illinois 
by the year 2000 the program has reached that goal already because 
we do have three pairs ms byre said 
once the chicago program ends the conservation department will 
evaluate whether to attempt peregrine release elsewhere in the 
state becker said 
