<TEXT>
the nature conservancy closed a deal 
monday to acquire the biologically diverse 321703acre gray ranch 
in new mexicos southwestern boot heel the environmental 
organization said 
it is the largest land acquisition in the nearly 40year history 
of the nonprofit conservancy which has protected more than 4 
million acres of ecologically significant land across the united 
states 
we acted as we did because we were concerned that it the 
ranch may be sold to another purchaser that may not share the kind 
of conservation goals that the nature conservancy had said bill 
waldman of santa fe director of the conservancys operations in 
new mexico 
more separate species and subspecies of mammals are found on 
the gray ranch than on any existing national wildlife refuge or 
national park in the continental united states waldman said from 
the groups national headquarters in arlington va 
the ranch supports an estimated 75 species and subspecies of 
mammals 150 species of birds and 52 kinds of reptiles and 
amphibians said michele merola operations and communications 
coordinator for the conservancy in santa fe 
the animals include three federally endangered species 
sanborns longnosed bat the bald eagle and the ridgenosed 
rattlesnake 
the state also has an endangered species list ms merola said 
and 21 plants and animals from that list are represented at the 
ranch including the whiteeared hummingbird the bunchgrass 
lizard nightblooming cereus greenflowered fishhook cactus and 
the white butterfly cactus 
in the middle of the ranch south of lordsburg sit the animas 
mountains covered with conifer trees like douglas fir pinon and 
juniper the flanks of the mountains give way to oak and shrub oak 
that is surrounded by semidesert grassland which makes up the 
bulk of the ranch 
last year congress postponed appropriations to buy the ranch 
and interior secretary manuel lujan jr placed an indefinite freeze 
on a proposed federal purchase of the ranch for use as a wildlife 
refuge 
lujans decision came after he and gov garrey carruthers toured 
the ranch last september at the time lujan expressed concern 
about its high cost 
the owners want 23 million but the appraisal is 16 million 
and by the time they buy surrounding ranches were looking at 50 
to 60 million instead lujan said 
the nature conservancy bought the ranch from gray land and 
cattle co which waldman said has owned the land for seven or 
eight years 
the price was not revealed but sen jeff bingaman dnm said 
last year that the group planned to buy the ranch for an estimated 
1825 million 
weve been actively involved in pursuit of protecting it for 
several years and weve been negotiating for two years waldman 
said 
the nature conservancy is acquiring 226664 acres of deeded 
land and will lease the remaining state private and us bureau 
of land management land waldman said 
the ranch was once the property of george hearst a california 
mining and livestock baron and father of publishing magnate william 
randolph hearst the conservancy said 
</TEXT>
