<TEXT>
the un human rights commission began its annual 
session on monday with a tribute to the late andrei sakharov who 
was hailed as a champion of freedom and human rights 
all members of the 43nation commission rose after the incumbent 
chairman marc bossuyt asked for a minute of silence in sakharovs 
memory and as a gesture of gratitutde for all those who 
courageously fought for human rights 
bossuyt a belgian international law expert also hailed the 
courage clearsightedness and selfsacrifice of political leaders 
who dared to abandon the methods of the past to confront realities 
in order to better respond to the needs of the peoples which 
they govern 
he said the past year had brought success for some human rights 
movements while others were drowned in blood 
in any case it is clear that the thirst for freedom can move 
masses throughout the world he said the last decade of the 
20th century has begun with that message 
bossuyt said he believed the commission remained silent on many 
past abuses too often every time a repressive regime collapses 
and human rights violations are revealed there is a certain 
embarrassment which some people try to hide in vain by feigning 
irgnorance he said 
the commission should concern itself less with the risk of 
displeasing some governments which violate human rights and should 
be more concerned by the fate of the victims of those violations 
he said 
jan martenson un undersecretarygeneral for human rights 
joined bossuyt in eulogizing sakharov we best honor his memory 
by maintaining the fight for justice and human dignity in the face 
of indifference and intolerance he said 
the crowded opening meeting was also attended by observers from 
many other un member nations and by representatives of more than 
100 nongovernmental organizations monitoring human rights 
purificacion quisumbing a senior legal official in the 
philippine government was elected to chair the 1989 session 
succeeding bossuyt 
the commissions agenda covers a wide range of issues from such 
traditional subjects as south africa and israel to special 
reports on a number of countries including iran and romania both 
nonmembers 
un secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar has been asked to 
submit a note on the situation in china a member the note is 
to come in response to a cautious resolution adopted by a panel of 
the commission last august following the brutal repression of 
prodemocracy protesters in beijing 
the united states has said it will make a new effort to have the 
commission launch a special inquiry into the human rights situation 
in cuba also a member of the commission 
</TEXT>
