<TEXT>
artist mel bolden figured his portrait of 
space shuttle challenger victim christa mcauliffe would circulate 
around the world but he didnt expect it to go into orbit 
he learned monday that a photograph released by the soviet news 
agency tass shows a copy of his mcauliffe poster on the wall in the 
soviet mir space station 
orbiting soviet cosmonauts featured the poster and an official 
nasa photograph of the challenger crew to commemorate their deaths 
four years ago sunday when the shuttle exploded shortly after 
launch 
im just trying to figure out how they got a copy of the 
poster bolden said its beyond my wildest dream or 
imagination 
its an honor he said im flabbergasted 
cosmonauts alexander serebrv and alexander viktorenko conducted 
a lesson for children from space sunday to commemorate the 
challenger anniversary 
mcauliffe a concord high school social studies teacher was 
chosen in 1985 from among 11000 teachers to be the first ordinary 
american to travel in space her main mission on the flight was to 
have been to conduct classes from orbit to rekindle interest in 
space travel 
boldens poster shows a smiling mcauliffe in her blue nasa 
flight suit the shuttle headed for space in the background it 
also incorporates a classroom scene painted in her concord high 
classroom 
on the blackboard is a simple message any dream can come true 
if you have the courage to work at it 
bolden who turned 71 on sunday the blast anniversary figures 
nasa may have given the soviets a copy of the poster 
bolden said he and mcauliffe worked together to design the 
poster which was intended to be distributed to help raise money 
for science scholarships 
we were trying to get across the idea of education 
particularly science education and trying to inspire kids into 
getting into science and math bolden said 
after mcauliffe died bolden took his idea to pepsicola co 
which bought the portrait and donated it to the smithsonian 
institutions air and space museum in washington 
the mir station was launched feb 20 1986 the current crew is 
the seventh to visit the station serebrv and viktorenko were 
launched into space in june for a planned sixmonth stay in mir 
</TEXT>
