<TEXT>
britains foreign secretary douglas hurd said 
monday he had urged the bush administration to grant american 
passports to residents of hong kong working for american firms in 
order to help the islands transition from british to chinese rule 
in 1997 
the idea is to reassure islanders that they can stay in hong 
kong while having a secure fallback of an american passport should 
they wish to leave hurd told reporters after lunching with 
secretary of state james a baker iii 
hurd was meeting president bush and other leaders on his first 
trip to washington since assuming office last october his talks 
were focused on upcoming changes within the nato alliance in light 
of the changes sweeping away the old order in the soviet union and 
eastern europe 
hurd said that if hong kong residents holding key positions 
leave the territory stability could not be maintained during the 
complicated transition period he said he told baker that it 
would be enormously helpful if the united states provided 
passports to islanders working for american firms 
britain and other countries would also be providing passports to 
hong kong residents under this scheme 
the subject will come up again tuesday when hurd holds talks in 
congress where legislation on the matter is pending 
hurd said he had appealed to baker for us understanding of his 
governments handling of more than 40000 vietnamese boat people in 
hong kong 
the british want to send most of the vietnamese back but the 
united states wants a oneyear suspension of the forced 
repatriation to vietnam 
hurd said the problem will become more accute with the 
anticipated arrival of 30000 to 40000 more vietnamese in hong 
kong this spring and summer 
he said british efforts were concentrated on explaining to 
residents of vietnam the realities of life in overcrowded camps in 
hong kong and other asian nations too many vietnamese are taken in 
by smugglers who tell them they are assured of resettlement in the 
west hurd said 
only about 1 percent of those leaving fit britains definition 
of refugees or people fleeing persecution the rest are viewed as 
economic migrants seeking a better life 
hurd said he had told baker that the british government is under 
pressure to launch an aid program for the communist government of 
vietnam to improve conditions in the impoverished country the 
united states has imposed economic sanctions on vietnam defying 
critics who argue that us economic help could do much to stem the 
flow of boat people 
hurd said the decision announced earlier in the day by defense 
secretary dick cheney to shut down dozens of military bases at home 
and abroad including pulling out of three royal air force bases in 
britain was compatible with natos objectives were satisfied 
that the decision is reasonable and compatible with the vienna 
talks between nato and the warsaw pact on reducing their 
conventional forces in europe as well he said 
hurd said he and baker generally agreed that although problems 
are clearly accumulating in the soviet union we dont see any 
reason to suppose they put a question mark over the leadership of 
soviet leader mikhail gorbachev 
</TEXT>
