<TEXT>
president bush asked congress on monday to 
close military bases while spending more money on the strategic 
defense initiative establish a new foreign aid program to 
encourage democracy in eastern europe and give families with 
longterm savings a tax break 
here are some of the highlights of the presidents 123 
trillion spending plan for the fiscal year beginning oct 1 
defense 
the budget would raise spending from 2963 billion this year to 
3033 billion in fiscal 1991 a 23 percent increase the defense 
department said that after inflation of 43 percent is figured in 
the change amounts to a 2 percent reduction the pentagon would cut 
38000 men and women from the 2 million now in uniform 
secretary of defense dick cheney proposed closing or realigning 
more than 60 military bases in the united states and 12 
installations overseas 
two army divisions would be disbanded by the end of the year 
they are the 2nd armored division at fort hood texas and the 9th 
infantry division at fort lewis wash 
the pentagon would also terminate 20 weapons programs in an 
attempt to save 29 billion 
the budget calls however for five new b2 stealth bombers at 
a cost of 55 billion and 900 million for the sdi program often 
dubbed star wars both proposals as well as the base closings are 
expected to encounter stiff congressional resistance 
therell be a debate about defense theres no question about 
that said speaker of the house thomas foley of washington 
also in the defense budget are 15 billion for another trident 
submarine and 202 million in continued financing of two landbased 
missile systems the railbased multiplewarhead mx and the 
truckbased singlewarhead midgetman another 17 billion would 
be spent for 52 submarinebased trident ii missiles 
foreign aid 
provides 300 million for democracies in eastern europe and 
calls for a nearly 80 percent increase to combat drugs including 
175 million to help drugproducing andean countries attack the 
narcotics problem 
proposes to begin the repayment over a fiveyear period of 
620 million in back dues owed to the united nations on top of 
794 million in current payments another 279 million would be 
earmarked for overdue bills from multilateral development banks 
the two largest recipients of us military and economic aid 
would continue at their current levels 3 billion for israel and 
21 billion for egypt 
taxes 
recommends 157 billion worth of tax increases but no general 
boost in income taxes there would be a 56 billion increase in 
user and service fees 
also included is a capitalgains tax cut and 18 billion in 
other tax reductions including a credit of up to 1000 a year for 
each child under age 4 in poor families social security tax 
receipts would be used only to pay off government debt beginning 
in 1993 
the interest paid on family savings accounts held for seven 
years would be exempt from income tax up to a limit of 5000 per 
joint tax return or 2500 per individual return after the seven 
years withdrawals would be tax free before that there would be a 
10 percent excise 
farm 
the budget provides 234 billion for nutrition the largest 
general program in the agriculture department budget including an 
increase of 600 million for food stamps to cover higher food costs 
and increased monthly allocations to families the food stamp 
budget would be 154 billion 
there would be less than 52 billion for child nutrition 
however down 156 million from 1990 despite the decrease 
children from the poorest families would continue to get meals free 
and those in middlelevel poverty would pay 20 cents a meal instead 
of 40 cents as at present 
children from affluent families now entitled to have meals 
subsidized by the government would have to pay full price adding 
about 29 cents per meal to their outlay 
the budget also provides more money for farm price support 
programs nevertheless guaranteed prices for farmers as well as 
the direct payments they receive for major crops would probably be 
reduced if congress goes along with 15 billion in commodity 
program cuts being proposed separately 
the budget could increase farm spending by about 41 per cent 
pushing it from the current 482 billion to about 502 billion 
on the other hand the increase could be held to 1 percent if the 
lawmakers approve the unspecified commodity cuts 
space 
increases the national aeronautics and space administrations 
spending from 12 billion to 141 billion or 24 percent the 
largest increase for any major agency of the government calls for 
a record 10 space shuttle flights next fiscal year at a cost of 
more than 8 billion the spending blueprint proposes budget 
authority of 26 billion for development of a manned space station 
and 12 billion for exploration activities to support a mission to 
the moon and later to mars 
transportation 
shifts much of the cost of air traffic control from direct 
federal spending to an aviation trust fund financed by user fees 
currently 3 billion comes from direct spending and 34 billion 
from the trust fund bush would cut the direct federal share to 
12 billion and raise the trust fund portion to 6 billion by 
increasing the user fees he said this would pay for 495 more air 
traffic controllers and 300 air safety specialists 
head start 
adds 500 million of spending authority for the preschool 
education program for a total of 19 billion the administration 
said the 36 percent increase should allow the program to enroll 
180000 more 4yearolds from lowincome families about 450000 
children now participate 
housing 
shifts nearly 60 million from lowincome rental programs to a 
certificate program designed to allow tenants of federally 
subsidized housing to buy their units the 23 billion housing and 
urban development budget also provides more money for urban 
enterprise zones designed to encourage selfhelp in the inner 
cities 
drugs 
boosts overall federal spending authority for the drug war by 
11 billion to 106 billion 
environment 
calls for 42 billion to clean up hazardous materials at 
department of energy nuclear plants and other facilities run by 
nasa and the departments of defense interior agriculture and 
transportation this would be an increase 642 million over the 
current fiscal year requests 175 million for the first year of a 
reforestation program aimed at planting 1 billion trees a year on 
private land 
arts 
increases spending for arts and humanities programs such as the 
national endowments and the national gallery of art and smithsonian 
institution from 694 million to 757 million the money includes 
2 million for an exhibit at the national gallery celebrating the 
500th anniversary of columbus voyage to america 
water projects 
no money is provided for new army corps of engineers projects 
the 32 billion budget for the agency is about the same as that 
for the current year the corps said the budget reflects the new 
emphasis placed by the administration on maintaining and restoring 
the environment 
</TEXT>
