<TEXT>
president bushs budget message monday 
suggested state and local governments build more toll roads to meet 
highway needs and charge air passenger fees to finance new airport 
construction 
a chapter of the fiscal 1991 budget document the administration 
sent to congress highlights efforts by states to come up with ideas 
to provide public services in the face of a shrinking federal 
ability to provide money 
it said local governments should encourage car pools including 
use of restricted lanes and turn to privately run city bus systems 
as an alternative to highercost public transit systems 
it recommends broader use of some of those state and local 
innovations and describes others as experiments worth watching in 
health care education the environment welfare and child care 
it is a picture of creative experimentation not social 
engineering but the natural flowering of variety inherent in a 
healthy federal system the budget report says of state and local 
efforts it is a picture that merits highlighting and federal 
government support 
the budget said states and local airport authorities are looking 
for alternatives to federal funding for expansion or construction 
and that a passenger facility charge is one prominent 
alternative 
congress prohibited such fees in 1973 but the administration 
will recommend congress pass legislation abolishing the ban the 
budget said 
a transportation department estimate said that by imposing a fee 
of 3 per passenger nearly 60 major airports would collect more 
than twice what they receive in federal airport formula grants 
toll roads while not a new idea have enjoyed a resurgence in 
popularity as federal highway money becomes more scarce federal 
law has prohibited use of federal money for construction of new 
toll roads but the government allowed several experimental 
projects in 1987 
the administration pointed to northern virginia where the state 
last year gave permission for investors to build a 14mile toll 
road the longest private toll road in the country 
for toll road users transportation costs will be higher but 
travel should be safer and quicker the budget said the 
administration will look favorably upon innovative means of 
financing highways including toll roads 
rae bond spokeswoman for the national governors association 
said that in highlighting state actions the administration did not 
address the governors call for the federal government to release 
some of the more than 16 billion accumulated in the highway trust 
fund 
the governors last summer asked the administration to release 
the money which is accumulating through federal excise taxes and 
the association contends could be used to pay for transportation 
needs in the states 
they appreciate the flexibility to do toll roads if thats 
appropriate and privatesector construction if thats appropriate 
but they have a concern about trying to force states to use toll 
roads or privatesector construction bond said the trust fund 
should be used first 
the budget said some cities have scaled back plans for rail 
rapid transit because of high construction costs and are 
substituting improved bus service 
private bus service has been successful sometimes for a portion 
of the total transit network the budget said adding that federal 
studies show private companies can operate 20 percent to 50 percent 
less expensively than public agencies largely because of lower 
labor costs 
it said carpools and use of buses should be encouraged as 
alternatives to mass transit and cited the approach in the 
virginia suburbs of washington where designated lanes of a primary 
commuter artery and an entire highway during rush hours are 
reserved for buses or carpools 
the budget cited a number of state programs aimed at encouraging 
poor youths to continue with their education including young 
welfare mothers and fathers 
among those it highlighted without endorsing was wisconsins 
controversial learnfare program which cuts welfare benefits if 
the familys children drop out of school 
it cited an oregan plan which will require a federal waiver of 
medicaid rules to expand health coverage to cover all whose 
incomes are below the poverty line 
while including more people oregon would limit cost by assuring 
only a basic package of medical services with additional 
medical services provided only if money is available the 
administration said the plan clearly breaks new ground in seeking 
to deal with a major problem and it is studying the idea 
</TEXT>
