a senate bill was introduced monday that would 
require telephone companies to allow customers to block caller 
id a new service that displays a callers phone number before 
the receiver is picked up 
sen herb kohl dwis said he was in favor of the new 
technology but that customers also should have the option of not 
giving out their phone numbers 
a privacy balance must be struck kohl said in introducing 
the telephone privacy act of 1990 
who decides whether the caller will reveal his or her 
number kohl said i think the decision must rest with the 
caller 
caller id which has been available in new jersey for more 
than a year and is just beginning to be offered in tennessee west 
virginia virginia pennsylvania and maryland uses a small 
terminal that displays the numbers of incoming calls the device 
costs 50 or more to purchase and the caller id service costs 
about 7 a month 
privacy rights advocates claim it is an orwellian intrusion on 
individual privacy unless a blocking option is offered phone 
companies such as bell atlantic which is phasing in caller id in 
the midatlantic states but not offering blocking say a blocking 
provision would defeat the purpose of the service 
california has passed legislation requiring blocking be offered 
with caller id and pennsylvania allows police and domestic 
violence agencies to block it some phone companies have said 
privacy concerns have delayed their plans to introduce the service 
kohl sits on the senate judiciary committee which according to 
congressional sources will consider caller id as part of 
hearings on a number of privacy issues this year 
kohl said he planned to sign up for the service whenever it is 
offered in his home district of milwaukee or in washington 
but there is a down side he said caller id will 
diminish our privacy as callers 
people with unlisted phone numbers are forced to divulge their 
numbers every time they contact someone who has caller id he 
said noting that a woman in a battered womens shelter may not 
want to reveal her number while calling her family 
under kohls bill calls to 911 emergency lines would not be 
blocked his bill does not specify however whether blocking 
should be offered on a percall or a subscription basis or whether 
it should be free 
david barasch consumer advocate of pennsylvania said he 
supported kohls bill and endorsed it on behalf of the national 
association of state utility consumer advocates kohls office said 
