president bush asked congress on monday for 
300 million in fiscal 1991 to reward emerging democracies in 
eastern europe and proposed major aid increases to andean countries 
to help stem drug production 
but the presidents overall 182 billion foreign affairs budget 
for the fiscal year that begins oct 1 was largely devoid of 
details including specific requests for most us aid recipients 
around the world and a description of exactly what bush wants to do 
in eastern europe 
also missing from the budget is any mention of panama 
the administration will seek a special appropriation this year 
to send about 500 million in cash and a like amount in noncash 
benefits to help the panamanian economy recover from us sanctions 
and invasion 
however the administration apparently has not decided what it 
wants to do for panama in fiscal 1991 
the 300 million for countries behind the crumbling iron curtain 
was billed as a special assistance initiative but appeared to 
some to be primarily the second installment of a threeyear aid 
package congress approved last year for poland and hungary 
a senate budget committee analysis called the proposal a cut 
from last year 
i dont see much for eastern europe to be frank said house 
budget committee chairman leon panetta dcalif 
senate foreign relations committee chairman claiborne pell 
dri was poised to introduce his own package of aid to the 
eastern european countries tuesday including easing trade 
restrictions and some direct aid 
it appeared likely that last years criticisms of bush as too 
timid toward eastern europe were likely to be replayed 
the budget document promised that legislation will be sent to 
capitol hill spelling out more clearly how the money would be used 
to encourage freemarket economic reform and development of 
democracy 
secretary of state james a baker iii who is still struggling 
with aid allocations for the current year is likely to be 
questioned about the administrations intentions when he testifies 
thursday before the senate foreign relations committee 
acknowledging that the bipolar superpower era is over the 
budget puts a new emphasis on international organizations that 
contrasts with the skepticism showed such groups by bushs 
predecessor ronald reagan 
bushs budget promises to pay off pastdue debts to the united 
nations and multilateral development banks left by reagan 620 
million in back dues to the un plus 794 million for the 
regularly scheduled payment and 279 million to clear a backlog 
for the banks 
a nearly 80 percent boost is proposed in aid for the war on 
drugs including 175 million in what the budget terms new aid 
for the economies of those countries that evidence a 
determination to attack seriously the narcotics problem 
under pressure from capitol hill the administration apparently 
is seeking some of that aid to help coca farmers switch to other 
crops coca is used to produce cocaine 
