<TEXT>
president bush on monday proposed a nearly 1 
billion increase in spending authority to modernize decrepit us 
nuclear weapons plants and clean up their environmental messes 
bushs proposed budget for the fiscal year beginning oct 1 
includes 995 billion for nuclear weapons development and 
production as well as environmental cleanup at the 17 major 
weapons facilities owned by the energy department 
that compares with slightly more than 9 billion currently 
allocated to the energy department for those purposes 
all the figures are for budget authority which represents 
ceilings on actual outlays to be determined separately the 
department used budget authority figures for the plant 
modernization project because funds are spent over several years 
under longterm contracts 
about twothirds of the proposed 1 billion increase is for 
energy secretary james d watkins new plan to clean up radioactive 
contamination and toxic wastes at the weapons plants and bring the 
facilities into compliance with environmental laws 
bush called for 275 billion in spending authority for cleanup 
and waste management for fiscal 1991 an increase of about 600 
million over current levels estimates of the total cleanup costs 
range from 65 billion to 100 billion in spending over 30 years 
watkins said most of the rest of the increase would go toward 
making nuclear weapons plants safer and more modern 
bush also proposed a 20 percent boost in spending on development 
of two new nuclear reactors to produce tritium a critical 
ingredient in nuclear warheads the new reactors would replace 
damaged facilities at the savannah river site near aiken sc 
watkins said its possible that only one new reactor would 
suffice but he stressed his view that no such cutback should be 
made until more is known about how reforms under way in the soviet 
union will affect western security interests 
watkins also confirmed that he decided to halt plans for 
building a hightechnology plutonium refinery in idaho the 12 
billion project known as the special isotope separation plant 
will be phased out starting april 1 he said 
the energy secretary said the department had determined that the 
idaho refinery was not needed to meet plutonium requirements for 
weapons production but that overall spending on the weapons 
complex must increase to meet defense needs 
until arms control is a fait accompli we have to demonstrate 
that we have the will to keep our strategic stockpile adequate 
watkins told a news conference 
he said a viable weapons production complex was as important as 
the warheads themselves in deterring a soviet attack 
watkins said the government had failed for years to invest 
adequately in nuclear weapons plants thus leaving them vulnerable 
to breakdowns and unsafe operation many key facilities are closed 
for safety and management improvements 
were trying to put the investment back in here to ensure that 
this doesnt become the achilles heel at the arms control 
bargaining table for the united states he said 
watkins also announced that a facility at the hanford nuclear 
reservation near richland wash that had been designed to 
provide plutonium for the space program would be shut down over 
four years beginning this year he said the department decided it 
would be cheaper for the savannah river plant to provide the 
plutonium 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

