the israeli government monday outlined a 313 
billion budget for 199091 that is intended to cope with a growing 
number of soviet jewish immigrants and hold the line on defense 
spending 
immigration and what it encompasses is determining the fate of 
this years budget finance minister shimon peres said in 
presenting the spending plan to the knesset or parliament for 
approval 
peres later told army radio israel has to think of other 
possible sources of money for absorbing immigrants 
the budget would increase the valueadded tax by one percentage 
point to 16 percent and hike taxes on fuel and cigarettes 
but peres rejected any other taxes or special assessments 
saying they could slow the pace of getting out of the recession 
and increase the rise in inflation 
parliament is expected to approve the budget with little debate 
or change 
the finance ministry said the proposed budget takes into account 
two main events the expected growth in the immigration from the 
soviet union and the stagnation in economic activity in 1989 
the economy grew just 1 percent each of the last two years and 
israeli officials have largely blamed the palestinian uprising 
against israeli rule in the occupied west bank and gaza strip 
under the proposed budget spending would grow by 53 billion 
or about 19 percent over the 198990 budget however when 
adjusted for inflation about 20 percent in 1989 there would be 
little change in real value 
