<TEXT>
the government reversed itself monday and shelved 
plans to use identity cards as a means of reducing violence at 
soccer games 
the decision was announced after publication of a report on the 
overcrowding that led to 95 spectators being crushed to death last 
april at hillsborough stadium in sheffield northern england 
judge peter taylor of the appeal court prepared the report 
which said using identity cards could cause crowding at turnstiles 
and more deaths by crushing 
prime minister margaret thatcher had supported the card idea 
against a host of critics in politics and the soccer world 
she indicated last week however that she would back down the 
reversal was confirmed monday when home secretary david waddington 
told parliament the government have decided not to proceed with 
the establishment of a football membership authority 
the authority was supposed to control hooliganism by issuing 
cards to fans that would admit them through computerized 
turnstiles the cards of known hooligans would have been 
invalidated 
among problems with the plan was the unresolved question of 
whether the courts or soccer authorities should decide who was a 
hooligan also the entire system would have had to operate through 
a central computer register whose ability to handle up to 400000 
fans a week never was established 
waddington said the legislation would stay on the books for 
possible activation if other methods failed 
abandonment of the card plan removes the cornerstone of the 
government antihooliganism strategy while britain is preparing to 
send teams from england and scotland to the world cup tournament in 
italy this summer 
hooliganism devastated english soccer in the 1980s with riots 
field invasions and street battles involving english fans abroad 
in the worst incident at a brussels stadium in 1985 39 people 
were killed when liverpool fans went on a rampage 
judge taylor recommended legislation to outlaw running onto 
soccer fields throwing objects from the stands or shouting obscene 
or racist remarks 
he also supported experimenting with surveillance of suspected 
hooligans by attaching electronic tracers to their legs but 
expressed grave doubts about the feasibility of the national 
membership scheme and serious misgivings about its likely impact on 
safety 
