the immediate losers were 68 journalists who worked for the 
pronoriega newspapers critica matutino and la republica they 
seek either reinstatment or severance pay but the publishers say 
the workers are not and never have been employees of panama america 
we are professional journalists said eva montillo former 
assistant editor of la republica we did our job as journalists 
the newspapers policy or ideology is something else 
aristides calvo editor in chief of editora renovacion as the 
company was called in the noriega years is the only journalist 
still detained by the new government complaints have been filed 
against him that include extortion and apology for crime 
endaras government has taken custody of at least 10 radio 
stations and two television stations owned by people believed to 
have been connected with noriega 
most continue operating government officials say they were 
taken over so investigations could determine whether public funds 
were used to buy them 
some may have to be returned including the largest television 
station channel 2 its owners include former pronoriega 
presidential candidate carlos duque and eduardo diaz herrera 
former secondincommand of the panamanian defense forces 
diaz herrera broke with noriega in mid1987 accusing the 
general of electoral fraud drug trafficking and other crimes 
less clear is the case of channel 5 which seemed to belong to 
whoever was president 
it first was owned by former president ricardo de la espriella 
whom noriega forced to resign 
when noriega made eric arturo delvalle president delvalle also 
got control of channel 5 when noriega had delvalle dumped the 
television station became the property of the government agency 
that had financed its purchase 
panama america may become a serious headache for the new 
