<TEXT>
fuel shortages like the one that may have 
occured before last weeks avianca crash are not routinely given 
emergency treatment unless the pilot actually declares a fuel 
emergency under federal rules for air traffic controllers 
fred farrar a spokesman for the federal aviation 
administration said monday that it is not the responsibility of 
the controllers to relay information other than the flights route 
and number unless the pilot specifically calls an emergency 
air traffic controllers have have one primary job to keep 
aircraft from getting too close farrar said its the 
captains job to fly the airplane its not the controllers job to 
make judgments for him 
however faa investigators said the regional controllers did 
relay information by telephone to the control center that handles 
approaches and departures at kennedy international airport but the 
urgency of the matter wasnt clear 
that conflicts with information provided sunday night by the 
national transportation safety board which said the regional 
controllers had not relayed word of the fuel shortage to the local 
controllers 
the regional controller said avianca 52 had just come out of the 
holding area and can only do five more minutes of hold can you 
take him now 
the local control replied slow him to 180 knots and i will 
take him 
under standards set by the faa if a pilot tells air traffic 
controllers he has minimum fuel both he and controllers know 
that no undue delay can be accepted 
but according to the faas air traffic control manual this is 
not an emergency situation but merely an advisory that indicates an 
emergency situation is possible should any undue delay occur 
a minimum fuel advisory does not imply a need for the aircraft 
to be given a traffic priority the faa rules state 
but if the pilot takes the next step and declares a fuel 
emergency the entire controller system is geared to help 
the faa manual puts it this way 
if at any time the remaining useable fuel supply suggests the 
need for traffic priority to ensure a safe landing the pilot 
should declare an emergency and report fuel remaining in minutes 
as he circled over the seaboard in holding patterns before 
crashing on long island the captain of avianca flight 52 never 
declared he had an actual fuel emergency 
the crash killed 73 people and injured 85 others 
on sunday lee dickinson of the national transportation safety 
board told a news conference in melville ny there was an 
apparent communications gap between highaltitude regional 
controllers and those handling landings 
as the plane neared the end of its final 46minute holding 
pattern south of kennedy international airport the crew told 
controllers in the regional new york center about the fuel shortage 
and requested priority clearance to land dickinson said 
shortly afterward the regional controllers turned the aircraft 
over to the local controllers but after interviewing six local 
controllers who either handled or tracked the flight investigators 
determined they were unaware of the shortage dickinson said 
r steve bell president of the national air traffic controllers 
association aflcio called the safety boards assrtions highly 
misleading and premature 
the avianca pilot never declared a fuel emergency he said 
no one knew how perilous was his situation until it was far 
too late bell said the air traffic controllers would have 
moved heaven and earth to make for a safe approach for the crippled 
aircraft but the pilot never sent out the key words that he was in 
mortal danger 
</TEXT>
