<TEXT>
when an ordinary man leading an ordinary life 
wakes up one morning to discover that he can fly his life is 
transformed right not in the fantasy world of randy cohen where 
people seldom have their feet on the ground 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
randy cohen isnt able to fly or live in a tree 
but he likes to think about it 
so cohen does the next best thing he writes about people who 
do 
his strangely talented people appear as a series of comic pieces 
in his book diary of a flying man published by knopf 
cohen a softspoken amiable 41yearold occupies an office in 
midtown manhattan that looks out on a building he regards as an 
architectural inconvience full of hardworking people no crimes 
being committed no affairs blossoming nothing 
the wall above his desk houses a large collection of pictures 
all of children a closer look reveals they are all of the same 
child its my daughter sophie 2 i took a lot of pictures of 
her so people would think i have a big family 
while in the office cohen works as a writer for the late 
night with david letterman television show he and nine other 
staff writers are responsible for generating amusing things the 
ongoing task that awaits weekly during his six years with the 
show cohen has come up with ideas as varied as attaching a 
miniature camera to a monkeys head and having him shoot the show 
that night as well as a musical piece trivializing glasnost 
the pieces in his book are not from the tv show the book is a 
lot darker and bleaker than the show but i like to think it is 
very very funny cohen says 
the title piece tells of an ordinary man leading an ordinary 
life who wakes up one morning and finds he can fly 
he exults mankinds oldest dream has become my reality i can 
fly this morning running after a 5 bill blowing along the 
pavement i simply lifted into the air what profound 
transformation will my life undergo unfortunately the five turned 
out to be a torn page from sundays fashion supplement 
which pretty well sums up cohens way of looking at things as 
he says the man believes the ability to fly will transform his 
life it doesnt instead of walking to the cash machine and 
finding it doesnt work now you can fly there and find it doesnt 
work i think that if all your dreams come true things would still 
be the same say you get superstrength so you lift up the phone 
book and order in a pizza then you tear the phone book in half 
big deal the pizza will still be cold when you get it assuming it 
arrives at all 
as for the men who live in trees the thesis is says cohen 
that men lead crude primitive lives and should be pathetically 
grateful that women invite them indoors left to their own devices 
men will revert to barbarism but the guys in the trees are happy 
they can eat food without sauces and throw their clothes on the 
floor in this case on the branches 
as one tree dweller puts it i dont have framed prints on the 
wall i dont give little dinner parties i havent ironed anything 
since 1973 what kind of life is that its my life 
here is an excerpt from one of the pieces in the diary its 
called sleep problems 
connies postal obsessions keep her up for hours i worry how 
long the lines will be at the post office tomorrow did i put 
enough postage on the letters i mailed today did i casually apply 
a stamp that will be worth thousands to collectors in 30 years is 
it unethical to use the rutherford b hayes commemorative when i 
disapprove of so many policies of his administration particularly 
his use of federal troops against striking railroad workers its 
all so trivial but my mind grinds on then i panic if i dont 
fall asleep right now tomorrow ill be too tired to get anything 
done at that point im doomed i get up put on my robe go into 
the living room phone someone i loathe and threaten them in a 
disguised voice usually this highpitched nasal twang 
cohen came to humor writing in a funny way 
i used to play drums in a rock n roll band and i could 
introduce a song with funny banter since i was a flamboyantly 
inadequate drummer it was suggested to me that i give up drums and 
become a standup comic so i became a freelance writer i sold my 
pieces and i made enough to eat modestly freelance writers are 
famous for low cholesterol 
he says he applied for a job with the letterman show when he 
found his wife planned to work at home and it terrified us that 
both of us would be at home i turned in a sample of my work sort 
of a comedy writing test and i was hired im sure it was a 
clerical error the piece i submitted can still conjure up visceral 
embarrassment at its inadequacies 
</TEXT>
