<TEXT>
robert urich believes theres more to the 
story of convicted wifekiller rob marshall than is revealed in his 
portrayal of marshall in the tv miniseries blind faith 
the twopart nbc series on sunday and monday is based on the joe 
mcginniss book about marshall who was sentenced to death on a 
charge of arranging for the murder of his wife in toms river nj 
in 1984 
i think this might be described as one scenario of what 
happened says urich its based on the book which is based on 
interviews im convinced theres more to it than comes out in the 
book or the miniseries 
but its not an actors job to make moral judgments about the 
character this is the first time ive played in a real documented 
story it bothered me that we might take license with the real 
story 
i play a man who says hes innocent the story is told from 
other peoples points of view if they say he looked suspicious or 
broke down and cried thats what i had to do overall i had 
problems of accurately nailing down his mood and tone 
urich has returned to california after ending his bostonbased 
role as the tough private detective in abcs spenser for hire 
he has sold his 20room 15acre home near boston and bought a 
smaller house in the san fernando valley 
last spring urich was seen as jake spoon a former law officer 
who also worked as an outlaw in the hit cbs miniseries lonesome 
dove he is now preparing for his first situation comedy since 
his brief appearance in soap 12 years ago 
it was knowing i was going to do a comedy that allowed me to 
do something as different and as dark as blind faith he says 
urich says he felt fortunate that roby marshall one of 
marshalls three sons acted as an adviser and was available on the 
set of blind faith 
this was a man who presented the picture of a perfect 
father urich says there was something compelling about this 
guy i did have the benefit of having his son roby by my side i 
felt i could believe him when he said his fathers hand shook or he 
lost his composure 
blind faith was adapted by john gay and directed by paul 
wendkos it also stars joanna kerns as robs wife maria david 
gray as roby jay underwood as son jay johnny galecki as son john 
dennis farina as prosecutor kevin kelly robin strasser as 
marshalls mistress felice richmond joe spano as marshalls best 
friend sal coccaro doris roberts as a friend of marshalls mother 
and william forsythe as the man who testified he arranged for 
marias murder 
as much as anything its a story of the survival of these 
boys and how this catastrophe affected their lives urich says 
after completing spenser for hire urich went to texas for 
his role in lonesome dove then he did movies for disney usa 
network and cbs 
spenser was based on robert parkers books about the tough 
boston detective 
the problem with spenser or any detective on a network is 
you cant really pinpoint the audience urich says you cant 
do the violence or the language or the elements necessary for the 
story spenser in the books was probably more ruthless but i felt 
america didnt need another hero who broke the law and all the 
rules 
in his new comedy american dreamer created by gary david 
goldberg family ties for nbc urich plays a former broadcast 
journalist named tom nash who returns to his hometown with his 
children after his wife is killed in a terrorist bombing he writes 
a column for a chicago newspaper 
i call it a version of our town for television he says 
its one mans reflection on life he brings along all his 
emotional baggage he stands in a spot of life and travels back and 
forth in time then a scene lights up and he steps into the action 
i play the role at all ages 
urichs last appearance in a theatrical film was in turk 182 
in 1985 although people remember him most for ice pirates in 
1984 
id like to do more features but ive managed to stay 
unavailable because of my work for television he says 
hes also acquired a small publishing company beaver dam press 
in nashville tenn and plans to reissue the outdoor books by 
nash buckingham 
