<TEXT>
in ohio students learned math in japanese after 
seeing a kabukistyle othello in new jersey a teacher used 
musical rhythms in a lesson on syllables in upstate new york a 
storytellers yarns brought a shy schoolboy out of his shell 
all were inspired by the lincoln center institute for the arts 
in education a program that brings a unique blend of culture 
academia and personal growth to thousands of students each year 
were not trying to teach respect or love for the arts said 
mark schubart director of the institute what were trying to do 
is more basic to teach about how people think and react and view 
the world 
each year the institute commissions a dozen productions 
including dance concerts and plays that are appropriate for 
children teachers preview the pieces on videotape and choose one 
for their school 
what makes the program special is the involvement of artists in 
the summer artists hold workshops at lincoln center to help 
teachers experience the creative process and to show them how to 
reach students through the arts in the fall the artists go into 
the classroom and help teachers prepare students for the production 
theyll be seeing 
in one workshop last summer composer john king had teachers 
clap sing and bang coffee cans to demonstrate contrapuntal 
techniques 
im not teaching them how to be musicians said king im 
teaching them how to look at music by experiencing rather than 
listening 
gail krehel a secondgrade reading teacher in paramus nj 
said she planned to use clapping to teach students how to divide 
words into syllables 
last fall elementary school students in new york city who were 
scheduled to see an adaptation of rudyard kiplings just so 
stories read the book discussed themes and characters played 
games to improve their concentration and acted out scenes to learn 
what its like to be a performer 
an actors got to change his voice and change his moving and 
his body and wear different clothes explained jesus mendez 7 
they dont look like real people when they have those things 
on said aaron tye 5 referring to the masks worn by the just 
so stories troupe 
aaron had worn a mask himself while portraying a dog during his 
classs improvisations i felt great i felt like an animal he 
said 
his classmate tavona cooper played a horse 
she came home and told me all about it said her mother 
donna she galloped around the house and showed me how the horse 
moves his hoofs 
cooper said she noticed a change in tavona since those 
improvisational sessions with an actress from the institute 
shes more outgoing more motivated now cooper said 
tavonas teacher gloria toro explained as theyre learning 
their selfesteem grows because theyre having so much fun and they 
love what theyre doing 
louise trucks of the aesthetic education institute in rochester 
which is affiliated with the lincoln center institute agreed 
children can learn things through the arts that they might not 
have found in other ways she said one child reached by the 
rochester program had been a withdrawn child not involved with 
other kids in the classroom until a storyteller began visiting the 
class 
by the time this storyteller left this boy was writing 
stories he was participating in the class telling stories and 
recruiting other children to do so she said 
the lincoln center institute began in 1976 with a handful of 
schools today the program reaches 100000 children in 289 schools 
in new york city long island westchester and rockland counties 
new jersey and connecticut the schools finance half the 
institutes 24 million annual budget the rest is paid by private 
and government grants 
programs modeled on the institute have sprung up in albany 
binghamton buffalo rochester syracuse and utica in new york as 
well as in san diego memphis and nashville tenn tulsa okla 
and other cities 
in bowling green ohio teachers used a kabukistyle performance 
of othello as a springboard for lessons on japan we had 
first graders doing arithmetic in japanese said director michael 
moore 
but the dividends are not solely academic were training kids 
how to ask aesthetic questions he said we have thirdgraders 
who can give critiques of plays we have kindergarteners who will 
sit through 90 minutes of a performance and not move were 
training people to be intelligent consumers of the arts 
barbara davis of the texas institute for the arts in education 
in houston agreed the children can relate to a contemporary 
dance piece or an opera she said its not just a bunch of 
people moving around on stage anymore 
</TEXT>
