<TEXT>
bob hover isnt sure what prompted a friend to tell him that a 
deteriorating old house standing empty in troy mich would be 
just right for him 
most likely it was because he had already turned a defunct fast 
food place into a nice restaurant in detroit says his wife jenny 
several months later he drove by the site and bob hover fell in 
love with the dunn homestead a late victorian clapboard house with 
gingerbread trim 
i had an immediate vision of how it would look when i had 
restored it recalls hover now more than a decade later his 
vision has been vindicated in january he won an award for the 
renovation from the national trust for historic preservation 
the hovers nowproud home of about 2700 square feet has a 
large living room dining room kitchen with new cabinets leaded 
glass cabinet fronts and a marble countertop four bedrooms two 
full baths a utility room and a full attic 
from the beginning hover an entrepreneur and an artist was 
convinced that he had the design and physical skills necessary to 
bring the house back to its former glory his willingness to tackle 
the restoration led delores dunnjohnson to sell it to him 
she and her sister irene dunnhouse were born in the homestead 
built by their grandfather terrence dunn in 1888 their memories 
old photos and other materials helped the hovers carry out the 
detective work necessary to rehabilitate the home delores johnson 
is now the hovers nearest neighbor 
when he bought the house and one acre for 40000 in 1979 bob 
knew it was going to take a long time to rehabilitate it i was 
26 and single so i didnt have to account to anyone 
the place had suffered substantial fire damage and had not been 
lived in for years it was in fact condemned by the town fire 
department 
he spent the first four years clearing away rubble filling a 
large dumpster 20 times with rubble from the site and running up a 
carting bill of about 4000 
town officials didnt think the house could be rebuilt and had 
scheduled it for demolition getting a building permit took four 
years and the help of the troy historic district commission and the 
two dunn granddaughters 
after the permit came through in january 1984 hover began the 
reconstruction work building professionals confirmed his opinion 
that virtually everything would have to be replaced he needed new 
plumbing electrical wiring and heating as well as a new roof 
kitchen appliances and walls 
all that was really left inside the house were the original 
doors some floors some hardware and the framing he recalls 
outside much of the trim was gone 
he set up a woodworking shop in what are now the living and 
dining rooms spending about 12000 on circular and band saws an 
industrial grade sander and router and a number of hand tools 
this enabled him to make all the wood components it would have 
cost tens of thousands of dollars to have the work done by somebody 
else he says 
he used existing woodworkoften brokenas patterns for 
exterior ornamentation wood frames and hoods for the 35 windows 
corbels corner blocks kitchen cabinets and newel posts for the 
staircase 
his father pete who is retired often helped him the work was 
done on weekends and most evenings from 4 to 11 pm hover did all 
the woodwork and painting but hired professionals to do the 
plumbing and electrical work and to lay the cedar shake roof 
the hovers moved into the house in 1987 a little prematurely 
they say in something of an understatement 
we didnt have a stove for seven months and the rooms were 
covered with plaster dust recalls mrs hover 
we weathered living with wild animals falling plaster no 
kitchen and several rooms with no floors a typical dinner 
consisted of peanut butter and sawdust sandwiches on our dining 
room table saw says hover 
in hindsight however his wife says the hardships have made 
them feel very tied to their new home which is now almost 
complete they are furnishing it in appropriate late victorian 
style with reproduction wallpaper lace curtains an old fashioned 
clawfoot bathtub and pedestal sink and victorian furniture 
one of the most difficult tasks in tackling a restoration 
project of this size was to secure the necessary financing 
convincing a bank that my boarded up condemned home was just a 
fixerupper was almost impossible says hover after getting a 
brushoff from several local banks hover was finally able to secure 
financing from his credit union which advanced funds in 
installments and checked on progress frequently 
hover says he has spent about 100000 in addition to the 
original purchase price a local real estate broker has estimated 
the property at about 170000 he says 
despite or perhaps because of all the hard work he put into 
his home bob hover looks back on the past decade as fun i loved 
doing the work from time to time i would take off a night or a 
weekend and i often wondered if i would be able to bring it off 
this was especially so when he had to redo work after 
reconstructing a staircase he realized it was in the wrong place 
so he ripped it out and rebuilt it in the right place 
every year he documented his progress with videotape and 
photos to remind him how far he had come with a project like 
this you need that kind of encouragement he says 
</TEXT>
