<DOCNO> AP900129-0209 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
you might not think of them as heroes yet some of the people 
who rehabilitate old buildings into homes are much like the 
american pioneers who blazed a trail across new territory 
robert hover wasnt daunted by the job of rehabilitating a 
condemned building swaying in the wind in troy mich for his work 
he won an award from the national trust for historic preservation 
the stories of the trusts 14 prizewinners and their projects 
could serve as a primer on house renovation 1990style 
an unusual chapter would be todd canterburys story he turned a 
76foothigh silo into a 3100squarefoot home in fairfax county 
va winning a first prize for adaptive reuse of a building 
robert hodges of baton rouge la not only rescued a derelict 
house and moved it to a new lot but resurrected the forgotten craft 
of bousillage to recreate authentic walls of mud and spanish moss 
also singled out were the restoration of a 1784 anglogerman 
stone house in virginia recreation of victorian detailing that 
had been stripped from a new york city apartment renovations to 
make a home accessible for a wheelchairbound occupant in 
philadelphia and restoration of beautiful pine woodwork in a texas 
home a job took five men five months and 11 55gallon drums of 
stripper 
the stories people wrote about what they did on their houses 
show they had a dream of what a house could be they did enormous 
amounts of research to make their dreams come true says anne 
powell editor of historic preservation the national trust 
magazine which pictures the winning entries in its winter issue 
there is an overall trend to be more meticulous 
the trust is planning a second competition 
the first contest brought 182 entries from 31 states the 
majority of entries 76 percent were submitted by homeowners 
themselves 
the judges noticed that many of the doityourself projects 
could not be distinguished from projects executed by highpriced 
professionals says clem labine one of the judges and founder of 
the oldhouse journal a publication which was at the vanguard of 
the restoration trend 
most of the homes dated from 1880 to 1895 although the oldest 
was built in 1672 and newest about 50 years ago economics are part 
of the growing interest in preserving late 19th century homes 
earlier homes have gotten more expensive and increasingly difficult 
to find as more people covet them early 20th century homes have 
become more desirable as the late 19th century places become more 
expensive 
the jewel in the rough that you could buy for 25000 and fix 
up is a thing of the past says labine the high cost of 
acquiring and redoing an old house is forcing some people to 
convert them to profitmaking properties such as bed and breakfast 
inns the historical bampb which didnt even exist 10 years ago 
is an avenue for people who want to own an old house but cant 
afford to 
redoing an old home with historical accuracy is creating an 
interest in architectural conservation many local history groups 
are changing their focus from genealogy to architecture according 
to labine 
an approach we see often is for owners to renovate a building 
itself with historic accuracy and furnish the interior in 
contemporary fashion he says at the opposite extreme is the 
period museum approach 
as a rule the more carried away you get with historical 
accuracy the greater the danger of committing the cardinal sin of 
real estate overimproving says labine you can spend a lot 
more money in restoration than by using conventional mainstream 
products from the local building center but some of the benefits 
of an accurate restoration are measured in quality of life rather 
than dollars and cents he says 
as restorer of an old house and former president of the old 
northside neighborhood association in indianapolis ind paul 
smith says the appeal of living in an old house is far more than an 
aesthetic appreciation for wonderful old detailing an important 
motivation is the sense of community in a neighborhood of old 
houses 
i can tell you the names of people who live seven or eight 
blocks away a common bond is that we are restoring an old house 
if i need a plumber i call my neighbor for the name of one who is 
sensitive to old houses he says 
the restoration trend has inspired an increase in the number of 
products available to do the work in 1976 there were 205 
suppliers of goods or services for restoration our current census 
found 1973 companies engaged in supplying products or services for 
sympathetic rehabilitation of old houses says labine 
and he notes preservation has become commercial because many 
people prefer old or quality reproduction homes the traditional 
buildings are sold out and the contemporary buildings are going 
begging in the marketplace the trusts second competition 
closes june 30 1990 for entry requirements and a nomination form 
send a selfaddressed stamped envelope to home awards the 
national trust for historic preservation 1785 massachusetts 
avenue nw washington dc 20036 
</TEXT>
