<TEXT>
bob hover says financing was the most serious problem he faced 
in his effort to rehabilitate a home in troy mich 
i looked into it but discovered there were no programs for 
which i qualified he says in order to get the funding the 
housing would have to be registered as a landmark 
according to ian spatz director of the center for preservation 
policy studies at the national trust for historic preservation 
federal tax incentives for historic preservation exclude 
owneroccupied buildings but they do apply to rental buildings 
such as bed and breakfasts or apartment buildings 
he says that a number of states and localities offer tax breaks 
or loans in connection with preservation programs but there is no 
central clearinghouse of information on these 
its up to the homeowner to call a local historic group or a 
state preservation agency to inquire if any tax grant loan or 
technical assistance programs exist at the city county or state 
level says spatz who tracks governmental policies on 
preservation as part of his job 
one of the more popular state programs is property tax 
abatement sometimes tied to income level of occupants and 
sometimes to the type of building or neighborhood he says this 
type of help is a local option in connecticut georgia oregon 
washington and illinois 
another typical incentive is a direct tax credit against state 
income tax in maryland says spatz localities are permitted to 
offer such a tax credit and in some owners can save 10 percent on 
property taxes if they spend at least 50000 on restoration in 
wisconsin a 25 percent tax credit is available and colorado is 
considering a similar guideline he says a state income tax saving 
is also available in new mexico and rhode island 
in each state restrictions are made according to the type of 
building and nature of the work standards usually allow changes 
for new use but require retention of basic historic features in 
many localities the building must be located within a historic 
district and be listed with the national register of historic 
places there are 700000 buildings within national register 
historic districts says spatz 
i am not aware of any program that gives you an incentive for 
just purchasing a historic building the incentives are all geared 
to fixing them up he says 
in some localities preservation organizations have loan 
programs a north carolina group for example uses a fund to buy 
historic places in danger of demolition and sells them to people 
who want to fix them up a sweat equity program in new orleans 
makes it possible for people who are willing to restore a building 
to own it the citys preservation resource center works with local 
banks to arrange financing according to spatz 
information if not funding is widely available to those who 
choose to rehabilitate an old building the oldhouse journal is a 
monthly magazine which covers most aspects of buying restoring and 
owning an old house call 18008889070 
the us department of the interior publishes the catalog of 
historic preservation publications which lists government 
pamphlets and books of interest to restorers of old houses its 
free and available from the departments preservation assistance 
division 1100 l street nw washington dc 20013 the national 
trust a private nonprofit organization supported by private funds 
membership dues and some government funding is one of the first 
places to turn for information members receive a monthly 
newsletter and bimonthly magazine and reduced fees for programs 
the national trust answers telephone queries on old house 
restoration conducts workshops and seminars all over the country 
and can put you in touch with preservation organizations in your 
area write to the group at 1785 massachusetts avenue nw 
washington dc 20036 phone 2026734000 
often the first question a prospective owner has concerns the 
property itself the first step should be a complete deed or title 
search in the countys records 
for urban areas sanborn maps that date back to 1867 can be 
invaluable copies of these maps are often found in libraries and 
historical societies which sometimes also can identify other 
sources of local historic information or old photographs that are 
helpful in reconstruction says the trust 
look in the public library for howto books on all aspects of 
old houses local landmark commissions often have information on 
buildings and districts under their jurisdictions and local 
newspapers may have old stories about fires involving the 
properties or obituaries of former owners 
</TEXT>
