<TEXT>
president bush is sending his first budget to 
congress today a 123 trillion spending plan that seeks to 
achieve former president reagans elusive goal of controlling the 
federal deficit 
bushs spending blueprint for the fiscal year that begins oct 1 
proposes slashing the deficit in half without violating his 
nonewtaxes campaign promise 
instead bush is offering to cut the capital gains tax which 
critics charge would benefit the wealthy and to create a new 
family savings account aimed at middleclass taxpayers who could 
squirrel away up to 5000 a year and earn taxfree interest 
bush is counting on a healthy economy to help boost government 
revenue in 1991 by 9 percent while he would hold the overall 
increase in spending to 3 percent he also would gain 139 billion 
in a variety of minor new taxes and user fees charged to provide 
government services 
savings would come in the pentagon budget where the 
administration is proposing a sweeping reordering of the nations 
defense priorities to reflect the lessening of eastwest tensions 
the governments huge medicare health program also would be 
targeted for reductions along with smaller cuts in such programs 
as farm subsidies lowincome energy assistance and college student 
loans 
bush would reallocate the money saved to boost spending on such 
programs as environmental protection education space and the war 
on drugs 
bushs budget calls for spending 1233 trillion in 1991 while 
projecting revenues of 1170 trillion that would leave a budget 
deficit of 631 billion which if realized would be the smallest 
amount of red ink since 1979 bush estimated the current years 
deficit at 1238 billion 
the projected 1991 deficit would be just below the 64 billion 
target established by the grammrudman law which mandates a 
balanced budget by 1993 bush said he would hit that target 
proposing a surplus of 57 billion that year 
the specific details on the budget were revealed in interviews 
and in documents obtained by the associated press 
even before the budget was released critics were accusing the 
administration of adopting an overly rosy economic scenario which 
inflates the amount of taxes the government is likely to take in 
while not calling bushs budget dead on arrival the epithet 
hurled at most of reagans spending plans democrats in congress 
left no doubt that they intended to challenge bush on many of the 
proposals 
senate budget committee chairman james sasser dtenn said the 
bush plan would get a very chilly and negative reaction on the 
hill 
the most bruising fights were likely to revolve around bushs 
renewed push for a cut in the capital gains tax and over a rival 
democratic proposal advanced by sen daniel moynihan dny to 
provide a 62 billion cut in social security taxes this year and 
next 
moynihan claims that the surpluses accumulating in the social 
security trust fund are being used to mask the real budget deficit 
rather than being saved for the baby boomers retirement 
bushs budget proposed an alternative plan to begin using a 
portion of the social security surpluses to reduce the national 
debt 
democrats also were upset with bushs military budget which 
proposed spending 3033 billion which amounted to a 2 percent cut 
when compared to the costs of inflation 
critics were unhappy because bushs budget proposed to reduce 
troops and civilian defense department employees by 38000 while 
protecting such pet projects as the strategic defense initiative 
nuclear shield 
to meet the pareddown spending levels the defense department 
was proposing a sweeping list of military base closings also a 
bone of contention with congress 
outside of the pentagon the biggest proposed reduction came in 
an 85 billion cut in the projected growth of the medicare program 
for the elderly and handicapped the money would be saved by 
cutting payments to hospitals and doctors but congress balked at a 
similar proposal last year 
bush proposed other cuts for farm programs and in payments to 
retired federal workers 
the budget also includes 
500 million more for head start the preschool program for 
poor children putting total spending at 19 billion 
an increase of 11 billion for the war on drugs boosting 
total spending to 106 billion 
a hefty increase in spending for the national aeronautics and 
space administration with gains also coming to fund development of 
the giant atomsmasher known as the supercollider 
new spending of more than 2 billion to fund an america the 
beautiful program that would accelerate the cleanup of hazardous 
waste dumps and launch a massive tree planting program to combat 
the effects of global warming 
the administrations proposed family savings accounts would 
allow individuals to invest up to 2500 a year and families to 
invest up to 5000 annually in taxfree savings accounts as long 
as the money was not withdrawn for at least seven years 
the administration seeking to counter a plan advanced by sen 
lloyd bentsen dtexas also proposed easing current restrictions 
on individual retirement accounts to allow savings to be withdrawn 
without penalty before retirement if the money was used for a 
firsttime purchase of a home 
bushs budget document represented his first full budget 
outline last february he submitted a 193page list of amendments 
to reagans final budget 
