<TEXT>
united auto workers union president owen bieber 
held out hope monday that fridays scheduled closing of chryslers 
corps jefferson avenue assembly plant in detroit could be put off 
bieber said the plants closing which will put about 1700 
people out of work will be among the issues he talks about tuesday 
with chrysler chairman lee iacocca and other company executives 
im always going to take advantage of one last day to make one 
more pitch to see if theres anything that can be done bieber 
said 
his chances of success are practically nonexistent the uaw 
earlier proposed that chrysler continue limited production of the 
dodge omni and plymouth horizon subcompacts at the plant and sell 
them to targeted groups of consumers chrysler rejected that plan 
chrysler and general motors corp have announced plant closings 
or production reductions that will result in the indefinite layoffs 
of more than 13000 auto workers by the end of march ford motor 
co has been able to avoid indefinite layoffs by trimming overtime 
and rotating temporary layoffs 
chrysler announced in november that its jefferson avenue 
assembly plant which has been making cars since 1907 and chrysler 
products since 1924 will be shut down feb 2 about two years 
earlier than planned 
the plant will be replaced in 1992 by the jefferson north plant 
now under construction next to the existing factory on detroits 
east side the new plant will make sportutility vehicles beginning 
for the 1993 model year 
chrysler invoked language in its contract with the uaw allowing 
it to close a plant when sales slip as has happened with the omni 
and horizon cars but the uaw is contesting the closing saying 
chrysler did too little to keep the cars introduced in the 1978 
model year alive 
bieber said he and iacocca have other topics to discuss 
we want to talk to them about the whole question of employment 
and job security whats going to happen to the workers not only at 
jefferson but at the others and the industry as a whole bieber 
said at a news conference before speaking to the economic club of 
detroit 
bieber tried to sidestep a question about bargaining priorities 
when the union opens talks with each of the big three automakers in 
july the uaw contracts with the automakers expire at midnight 
sept 14 
the leader of the 1millionmember union said bargaining 
priorities will be set at a special uaw bargaining convention 
beginning may 21 in kansas city mo 
however he said obviously job security has got to be an 
issue that i feel very comfortable the delegates are going to say 
is of primary importance so job security has got to be no 1 
bieber also reiterated the unions support for a national 
healthcare program for years automakers have complained about 
soaring worker healthcare costs and some automakers have 
estimated that health insurance programs add hundreds of dollars to 
the price of every new car 
