<TEXT>
energy futures prices rose monday with wholesale 
home heating oil posting particularly strong gains 
the contract for february delivery of no 2 heating oil closed 
151 cents higher at 6111 cents a gallon on the new york 
mercantile exchange rebounding from fridays decline of 017 cent 
the march and april contracts ended with similar increases 
among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange 
february wholesale unleaded regular gasoline finished up 070 cent 
at 6282 cents a gallon adding to fridays gain of 152 cents 
contracts for later delivery also advanced but more moderately 
crude oil extended its rally into a third straight session after 
reaching a low of 2160 a barrel during thursdays trading the 
march contract for west texas intermediate the benchmark grade of 
us crude oil closed at 2280 per 42gallon barrel up 24 cents 
the contract had gone up 32 cents on friday 
contracts for delivery of west texas intermediate during april 
through june rose by 30 cents to 34 cents a barrel 
the strength in the crude oil trading pits partly reflected 
speculation about future refiner demand said andrew lebow a 
broker at edampf man international futures inc 
some of the buying was due to internal market dynamics such as 
short covering he said noting that it was difficult to pinpoint 
specific reasons why energy prices were bid higher short covering 
involves buying back a previously sold commodity 
