soybean futures prices rebounded sharply monday from 
lifeofcontract lows in a move that could mark a turnaround in the 
market after a sixweek slide 
most grain futures also advanced on the chicago board of trade 
on other commodity markets oil futures rose strongly pork bellies 
posted limit losses while livestock futures were mixed and 
precious metals declined 
soybean futures settled 5 cents to 8 cents higher in chicago 
with the contract for delivery in march up 5 cents at 563 a 
bushel 
wheat futures ended 2 cents lower to 1 cents higher with march 
at 378 a bushel corn was cent to 1 cents higher with march 
at 239 a bushel oats were 1 cent higher across the board with 
march at 138 a bushel 
during the session march soybeans traded as low as 553 a 
bushel eclipsing the contracts previous low of 557 but 
finished above the previous sessions high of 561 
technical analysts call such a performance a key reversal 
it often signals the end of a longterm trend 
if youre going to look for places to buy the market i think 
this is it at least for a little while said pat oconnell 
grains analyst with the futures brokerage refco inc in chicago 
wheat and corn futures also closed above their lows for the day 
but analysts said those reversals were less significant than the 
soybean markets performance 
soybeans had opened mixed with selling pressure stemming from 
reports of beneficial rain over the weekend in the soybean fields 
of argentina the market made its lows before noon cst then headed 
higher along with the wheat market which was rallying strongly on 
its own technical signals 
wheats rally stalled but the soybeans kept climbing into the 
close 
when the key reversal was established the market just fed on 
itself said anne frick senior oilseed analyst with 
prudentialbache securities inc in new york 
thats what gave us that extra 2 cents or so that little push 
up to the final high for the day she said 
wheat and soybean futures prices have been slipping since 
middecember due to a lack of export demand and improved growing 
conditions for winter wheat and the south american soybean crop 
soybean and corn traders will soon begin to focus on crop 
weather in the corn belt where planting begins in about three 
months a 90day forecast issued monday by the national weather 
service predicted drierthannormal weather for western corn belt 
states through the end of april which could be a supportive signal 
for prices 
