<TEXT>
us sprint said monday some customers 
will be able to place longdistance calls with their voices by 
summer in what would be the first voiceactivated dialing offered 
by a longdistance company 
sprint said the new service targeted toward business travelers 
would allow a caller to use a spoken password instead of a standard 
longdistance travel card which requires callers to punch in as 
many as 24 digits 
in addition a caller could speeddial certain preregistered 
numbers by saying passwords such as call home into a phone 
the company said the new system would provide greater security 
against unauthorized use of calling cards by ensuring the callers 
voice matched a preregistered voice pattern 
these are the features the tells us they 
want said sydtraveling public courson spokesman for kansas citybased 
sprint 
the nations thirdlargest longdistance company 
sprint unveiled the service sunday in commercials broadcast 
during the super bowl 
american telephone amp telegraph co said it has the technology to 
offer similar voiceactivated services and is doing trials to 
determine what specific features are in demand atampt spokeswoman 
fran anderson said some products could be announced in 1990 
a spokesman for mci communt system will be available to several hundred 
thousand customers by early this summer but courson would not 
specify what markets would get it first or what it would cost 
testing on the system began in december 1988 said larry lake 
senior vice president of product management 
us sprint which controls about 8 percent of the domestic 
longdistance market is an 80percentowned subsidiary of united 
telecommunications inc of kansas city gte corp of stamford 
conn owns the remaining 20 percent 
