about onethird of the workers at ford motor 
cos plant outside mexico city returned to work monday after a 
labor dispute that sparked a 22day shutdown a ford spokesman said 
spokesman carlos bandala said 1200 union employees went back to 
work at the cuautitlan plant 15 miles north of mexico city and 
another 1200 were expected to rejoin the labor force tuesday 
we expect to resume full operation probably by the end of this 
week bandala said 
the 3800member work force produces 450 cars and trucks a day 
for the mexican market under normal conditions current production 
figures were unavailable he said 
one worker was killed and nine others injured in a jan 8 
confrontation among employees at the plant between 150 and 200 
people entered the plant and shot and beat workers as they arrived 
for the morning shift ford closed the plant saying there was no 
security for workers 
after the flareup protesting unionists took over ford 
installations demanding the ouster of union leader hector uriarte 
authorities issued an arrest warrant charging uriarte with 
masterminding the violence 
newspaper reports monday said dissident union members were 
maintaining a picket outside the company installations 
