<TEXT>
a delaware court has ruled that the 
board of resorts international inc then headed by donald trump 
acted in good faith when it approved a 36ashare offer by 
entertainer merv griffin 
trump hailed the ruling as a great victory and said it would 
forestall any attempt by resorts bondholders to sue him but an 
attorney for some bondholders disputed that contention 
in a decision reached friday but announced monday the delaware 
supreme court court upheld a lower courts ruling that it was 
doubtful any objecting shareholders could prove the board of 
directors committee acted with gross negligence or bad faith in 
approving griffins bid in june 1988 
the court also dismissed the contention of shareholders who said 
they did not benefit from the deal between griffin and trump the 
court said they received 36 a share from griffin when trump had 
offered only 22 a share 
resorts is incorporated in delaware 
trump had been resorts chairman and controlling stockholder 
before griffin bought the casino company taking on more than 900 
million in debt and issuing bonds to finance that debt 
trump was paid 637 million to break his management contract 
with resorts he also received the unfinished taj mahal casino for 
250 million half the 500 million resorts had sunk into 
construction 
in a telephone interview from new york trump called the 
decision a great victory and said it would end speculation 
about disgruntled bondholders suing trump for alleged fradulent 
conveyances 
were really very happy about it trump said it puts to 
rest any loose ends 
as part of a bankruptcy reorganization plan filed late last year 
in us bankruptcy court in camden by resorts international 
griffin set aside a 5 million kitty for possible legal action 
against trump 
attorneys for some bondholder groups had said they might sue 
trump for fraudulent conveyance 
resorts attorney tom gallagher said the decision would not have 
any impact on the reorganization plan 
the ruling is as expected gallagher said theres nothing 
new in it 
marc s kirschner an attorney for some resorts bondholders 
discounted the importance of the ruling 
i think its irrelevant he said it has to do with 
shareholder rights and remedies and has zero to do with creditor 
rights and remedies 
most analysts say griffin paid too much for resorts and burdened 
his purchase with too much debt estimated at about 912 million 
griffins bankruptcy plan which still must win approval from 
bondholders and state gaming regulators would have him exchange 78 
percent of his equity in the company for about twothirds of the 
outstanding debt 
the win or gross profits for resorts dropped last year to 
2274 million from the 2429 million posted in 1988 according to 
the state casino control commission 
